 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 e5 { Black always has the option to transpose to a Scheveningen setup with 6...e6 instead. This repertoire, however, recommends the more solid 6...e5 whenever this is possible, which means: Whenever White cannot gain an advantage by playing 7. Nf5 in response. } 7.Nb3 ( 7.Nf5 $6 Bxf5 ( { In this particular position, also good is } 7...d5 8.Bg5 $2 d4 9.Nd5 Bxf5 10.Bxf6 gxf6 11.Qf3 Be6 12.Nxf6+ Ke7 $19 ) 8.exf5 d5 $15 { Whenever this sequence (Bxf5 and d6-d5) is possible, 6...e5 is a good move for Black. } ) 7...Be6 { As a general rule, when White plays his bishop to e2, Black should play Be7. When White plays his bishop to e3, Black should play Be6. } 8.Be2 Be7 9.f4 { Now White is threatening f4-f5 and we can see why Black should not play Be6 before White has moved his dark-squared bishop: Now White's bishop is forced to move for a second time. } 9...exf4 10.Bxf4 Nc6 11.O-O O-O 12.Kh1 Rc8 $1 ( { Also satisfactory for Black is } 12...Ne5 $5 13.Nd4 Rc8 14.Nxe6 fxe6 15.Bxe5 dxe5 16.Qxd8 Rfxd8 17.Bd3 Kf7 18.Rad1 Bc5 { , with good central control. } ) ( 12...b5 $6 { is rarely a good move in positions after Black plays exf4: } 13.Bf3 Rc8 14.Nd5 Bxd5 15.exd5 Ne5 16.Nd4 { Due to the weakening of the c6-square, White's d4-knight is threatening to become very strong. } ) 13.Nd4 Nxd4 $1 14.Qxd4 Qc7 15.Bf3 ( 15.e5 $6 dxe5 16.Bxe5 Qc5 $15 ) 15...Nd7 16.Rac1 { Now Black's central outpost looks more useful than White's: } 16...Ne5 17.Nd5 Bxd5 18.exd5 Bf6 { For the remaining game, White's light-squared bishop will be the weakest minor piece on the board. If he somehow manages to defend against the various tactical threats against the queen and his b2-pawn, Black will still have the pleasant choice between a minority attack on the queenside and pushing his kingside majority after Rae8, g7-g6, Bg7 and f7-f5. } 

