 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.g3 Nbd7 9.Bg2 Be7 ( { Unfortunately, } 9...Bc4 { fails due to } 10.Nd2 ) 10.O-O O-O 11.Nd5 { Now White is threatening c2-c4 (remember, we already prevented this on move 4!) . To keep him from taking back with the c-pawn and achieving a huge advantage, Black has to trade immediately. } 11...Bxd5 ( { This is one of the positions where } 11...Nxd5 $5 { can be considered: } 12.exd5 Bf5 13.c3 Bg6 $1 $132 { , followed by f7-f5. } ) 12.exd5 Rc8 { Not only developing the rook to its logical square but also slowing down White's play by preventing c2-c4 for the moment. } ( 12...b5 $6 { is premature in view of } 13.a4 $1 $14 { , and Black's b-pawn becomes a target. } ) 13.c3 Ne8 $1 14.Nd2 f5 $13 ( { Also interesting is } 14...Bg5 $5 { , as the trade of dark-squared bishops would clearly favour Black here. } ) 

