 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Be3 Be6 10.f4 exf4 $1 11.Bxf4 Nc6 12.Bf3 Rc8 13.Nd5 Bxd5 14.exd5 Ne5 15.Nd4 ( { After } 15.Bxe5 $2 dxe5 { , Black's pawn majority is much faster, for example: } 16.Qd2 Ne8 17.Kh1 ( 17.Rae1 Bd6 18.Be4 g6 19.g4 Ng7 ) 17...f5 18.c3 Nd6 19.Rae1 Bf6 ( 19...e4 20.Be2 Bf6 21.Nd4 Bxd4 22.Qxd4 ) 20.Be2 g6 21.Bd3 Bg7 $17 ) 15...Nfd7 $15 { As is often the case in this pawn structure, White's light-squared bishop is the weakest minor piece on the board and with every trade, this will become more of a problem. } ( 15...Qb6 $17 16.b3 Nxf3+ 17.Rxf3 Nxd5 ) 16.Kh1 ( 16.Nf5 $6 { is simply met by } 16...Bf6 { , and the d-pawn is indirectly protected: } 17.Nxd6 $4 Qb6+ ) 16...g6 ( { Also good is } 16...Bg5 $15 { , as the trade of bishops would underline Black's dominance on the dark squares. } ) 17.c3 ( 17.Bh6 { achieves less than nothing: } 17...Re8 18.Be2 Bg5 $1 19.Bxg5 Qxg5 20.Nf3 Nxf3 21.Bxf3 Ne5 22.Be2 f5 $17 ) 17...Bf6 ( 17...Bg5 $5 ) 18.Qc2 Re8 19.Rae1 Bg7 $15 { Now some white players may seek refuge in an opposite-coloured bishops position, but with queens on the board, there is no drawish tendency. Quite the contrary, Black's bishop is mobile and has the potential to become a strong attacking piece, for example } 20.Bxe5 Nxe5 21.Be2 Qc7 22.Nf3 Nxf3 23.Bxf3 Be5 24.h3 h5 $17 { The prospect of the black queen appearing on f4 or g3 is quite scary for White and will be for a long time, as this one-sided game is unlikely to end soon. } 

