 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Bg5 Be6 10.Bxf6 { The only way for the bishop to exert control over d5 is to take on f6 immediately, before a knight can recapture. } ( 10.Qd2 $6 Nbd7 { The bishop is doing nothing on g5 and even preventing White from playing Nd5 at some point. } 11.Bxf6 $2 Nxf6 $17 { Black is clearly better, for example } 12.f4 exf4 13.Rxf4 Rc8 ( { Or } 13...Nd7 14.Rff1 Ne5 15.Nd5 Bg5 $17 ) 14.Nd5 Bxd5 15.exd5 Nd7 16.Rff1 Ne5 17.Kh1 Bg5 18.Qd1 g6 19.Nd4 Bh6 20.Bg4 Ra8 21.c3 Qb6 22.Rb1 Rae8 ) 10...Bxf6 11.Nd5 Nd7 12.Nxf6+ $2 ( 12.Qd3 Bg5 13.c3 Rc8 14.Rfd1 Kh8 15.Ne3 $132 ) 12...Nxf6 13.Bf3 Qc7 $15 { As often in these positions White's light-squared bishop is a sorry sight. Now Black should not hurry to execute the d6-d5 break. The d6-pawn will never be in real danger, as it can be easily protected by a rook, and later, when the queens are exchanged, even more securely by the king on e7. } ( 13...d5 $2 { Solving the opponent's main problem is rarely a good idea. } 14.exd5 Bxd5 15.Bxd5 Qxd5 16.Qxd5 Nxd5 17.Rfd1 $11 ) 14.Re1 Rac8 15.c3 Rfd8 16.Qc2 b5 17.a3 Qb6 18.Rad1 a5 19.h3 g6 { As White lacks counterplay Black has time to secure his king before continuing the minority attack. } 20.Kh1 h5 21.Kg1 Kg7 22.Nd2 Rc7 23.Be2 b4 $17 

