 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 a6 $1 { It is important to prevent a transposition into a different open Sicilian if White decides to opt for a quick Nf3 and d2-d4 after all. } 3.Nf3 d6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 Nf6 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.Be2 Be7 9.f3 { Combining this move with Be2 is hardly ever a good idea. f2-f3 prepares the so-called English Attack g2-g4-g5 (possibly with h2-h4-h5 inserted, to prevent Nh5) . In this case White always castles long and the bishop on e2 (that was supposed to prepare short castling) constitutes the loss of an important tempo. } 9...O-O 10.g4 $2 { With the king still on e1, this is clearly premature. } 10...d5 $1 $17 { The classical way: Meeting early flank activity with a central counter. } 11.g5 ( 11.exd5 Nxd5 12.Nxd5 Bh4+ $1 $17 13.Bf2 Bxf2+ 14.Kxf2 Bxd5 15.c4 Qh4+ 16.Kg2 $2 Qxg4+ $19 ) 11...d4 $1 12.gxf6 Bxf6 13.Bf2 ( 13.Bd2 dxc3 14.Bxc3 Bh4+ 15.Kf1 Bh3+ 16.Kg1 Qg5# ) 13...dxc3 14.Qxd8 Rxd8 15.bxc3 Nd7 $17 { White cannot hold on to the c3-pawn, and the rest of the queenside is also fractured an weak. } 

