 1.e4 $1 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.Be2 Be7 9.O-O O-O 10.Qd3 Nbd7 11.Nd5 { The idea behind Qd3. Not only are the rooks connected, but Black can also no longer take on d5 with the knight without losing material. Fortunately for him, taking with the bishop is the standard move and fully satisfactorily anyway. } 11...Bxd5 12.exd5 Rc8 ( { Again, } 12...b5 { is premature: } 13.a4 b4 14.Qd2 a5 15.Bb5 $14 ) 13.c4 b6 $1 14.a4 a5 $1 15.Nd2 Nc5 $1 16.Bxc5 bxc5 17.Ne4 Nxe4 18.Qxe4 f5 19.Qc2 e4 ( 19...g6 20.f3 Bf6 $15 ) 20.Rad1 Bf6 21.b3 Be5 $17 { The difference in strenght between the two bishops is obvious. } 

