 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.f4 $2 { This weakens the e4-pawn prematurely and Black will develop accordingly: } 9...b5 $1 { The general rule is: Don't play this before finishing development. But this is an exception. b5-b4 is a threat and the bishop will be developed to b7, to increase the pressure against e4. } 10.a3 ( { Or } 10.a4 b4 11.Nd5 Nbd7 12.Kh1 ( 12.Nxb4 $4 Qb6+ ) 12...Bb7 $15 ) 10...Bb7 11.Bf3 Nbd7 { The ideal setup in the Najdorf if White plays f4. Unfortunately, Black can only achieve it if White goes wrong - see part 1 of this lecture: "The early b7-b5 advance". } 12.f5 a5 $1 $17 ( { Another interesting idea is } 12...Rc8 $5 { , preparing the standard exchange sacrifice } 13.g4 $6 Rxc3 14.bxc3 Nxe4 15.Qe1 Bh4 $1 $17 ) ( { Less good is } 12...Nb6 $6 { as it fails to keep an eye on a5 for a single moment: } 13.Na5 Qc7 14.Nxb7 Qxb7 $14 ) 13.Re1 b4 14.Nd5 Nxd5 15.exd5 Nb6 16.axb4 axb4 17.Ra5 Ba6 18.Be2 Bxe2 19.Rxe2 Qc8 20.Rb5 Qa6 21.Rxb4 Nxd5 22.Rg4 Nf6 23.Rg3 Kh8 24.Rh3 Rfc8 25.Bd2 Rxc2 26.Qxc2 Qxe2 27.Rc3 Ng4 28.Qb1 Bd8 29.h3 Bb6+ 30.Kh1 Nf2+ 31.Kh2 Ne4 32.Qa2 Rd8 33.Rc6 Bf2 34.Rc1 Nxd2 35.Qa5 Nf3+ 36.Kh1 Rg8 37.Qd5 Ne1 

