 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.h3 e5 7.Nf3 Qc7 8.Bg5 Nbd7 9.a4 b6 $2 { A typical mistake in this kind of position. Black should play this queenside fianchetto only after the e4-pawn is weakened. } ( 9...h6 $1 10.Bh4 ( 10.Be3 Nc5 11.Nd2 Be6 $132 ) 10...g5 $1 ( { Of course not } 10...b6 $2 11.Nd2 Bb7 12.Bc4 $16 ) 11.Bg3 Nc5 12.Nd2 Be6 $132 { This is one of the very rare cases where Black can even consider long castling in the Najdorf. } ) 10.Nd2 $1 Bb7 11.Bc4 Be7 12.Qe2 O-O 13.O-O $16 { Black has no convincing plan here. The e4-pawn is safe and can always be further fortified with f2-f3 if the need arises. On the other hand, the fianchetto has created a weakness on a6, which ties a rook to its protection. } 13...h6 14.Bh4 ( 14.Bxf6 $1 $16 { This is even better. } 14...Nxf6 15.Rfd1 Rfd8 ( 15...Rfc8 16.Bb3 Bc6 17.Nc4 ( { Or } 17.Nf1 Qb7 18.Nd5 Nxd5 19.Bxd5 Bxd5 20.Rxd5 Qc6 21.c3 $18 ) 17...Nxe4 18.Nxe4 d5 19.Nxb6 Qxb6 20.Nc3 d4 21.Nd5 Bxd5 22.Bxd5 Ra7 23.Qxe5 $18 ) 16.Nf1 $16 ) 14...g5 15.Bg3 Nc5 16.Rfd1 Ne6 17.f3 Nd4 18.Qd3 Nd7 19.Bf2 Nc5 20.Qf1 Nxc2 21.Rac1 Nb4 22.Nd5 Bxd5 23.Bxd5 Nxd5 24.exd5 Qd7 25.Nc4 Nxa4 26.b3 b5 27.Na5 Nc5 28.b4 Na4 29.Nc6 Bf6 30.Qd3 Bg7 31.Qf5 Qxf5 32.Ne7+ Kh7 33.Nxf5 Rfc8 34.Rxc8 Rxc8 35.Nxd6 Rd8 36.Nb7 Rb8 37.Nc5 Nc3 38.Rd2 Ne2+ 39.Rxe2 f5 40.d6 Rd8 41.Rd2 Bf8 42.Ne6 Bxd6 43.Nxd8 Bf8 44.Nc6 e4 45.fxe4 fxe4 46.Ra2 g4 47.hxg4 Kg6 48.Rxa6 Kg5 49.Ne5 Kf4 50.Ng6+ Kg5 51.Nxf8 Kxg4 52.Ne6 Kf5 53.Nd4+ Ke5 54.Nxb5 Kd5 55.Be3 Kc4 56.Nd6+ Kd5 57.Nxe4 Kc4 58.Rxh6 Kd5 59.Rh4 Kc4 60.Rf4 Kd3 61.g4 Kc4 62.g5 Kd3 63.g6 Kc4 64.g7 Kd3 65.g8=Q Kc2 66.Qc4+ Kb2 67.Rf2+ Kb1 68.Qc1# 

