 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Be3 Nbd7 $2 { How can White exploit Black's mistake? } ( 9...Be6 { is the correct move. } ) 10.f4 $2 { This is a terribe strategic mistake, justifying Black's delayed development of the light-squared bishop. } ( 10.a4 $1 $16 { Suddenly Black has no constructive moves, since after } 10...Qc7 ( 10...b6 $6 11.Nd2 Bb7 12.Bc4 $16 { offers White a strong grip on the light squares and no counterplay to combat it. } ) 11.a5 Nc5 { , White's knight proves to be much better on b3 than on f3: } 12.Nxc5 dxc5 13.Bc4 $1 $16 ) 10...b5 $15 { And after his opening mistake went unpunished, Black has the perfect setup. } 11.Bf3 Bb7 12.a3 Rc8 13.Kh1 Re8 $17 

