 { [%evp 0,14,22,43,49,48,68,57,57,23,46,35,61,31,31,39,45] It is time to start looking at the concrete theory. In this lecture, I will explain the subtleties of the move 6.Be2. The starting position arises after the moves: } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 { Here, I suggest the move: } 6...e5 { I believe this approach is more ambitious than 6...e6. White is at a crossroad: to play 7.Nf3 or 7.Nb3 After: } 7.Nb3 ( 7.Nf3 { Is a tricky and exciting alternative. Black needs to know exactly what to do. The best reaction is: } 7...Be7 8.Bg5 Nbd7 { and the practice shows that Black is doing OK here. } ) 7...Be7 $1 { Black's plan is simple: He wants to castle quickly, develop by means of Be6 followed by Nbd7, and start his typical queenside play. Usually, the game is positional in those lines, with many maneuvres for both sides. White has two typical plans: 1.Playing f2-f4 2. Jumping Nd5 followed by exd5 and starts advancing his queenside majority. I analyze many games here, and I believe that after studying them carefully, you should feel comfortable in these positions. } 

*

[Date "2022.11.11"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[ECO "B92"]
[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[EventDate "2022.??.??"]
