[White "6.Be2-e5 VARIATION"]
[Result "*"]
[Site "?"]

 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 { This simple move has always been popular. Whenever we can we choose the classical Najdorf approach with ...e7-e5 and not the Scheveningen set-up with ...e6, which in fact is also perfectly playable and good! } 6...e5 7.Nb3 ( 7.Nf3 $5 { This is an interesting and tricky alternative. Black must know what to do!! } 7...Be7 $1 ( 7...h6 $5 { This is the lazy man's solution. We play ...h6 intending ...Be6 and normal Najdorf development, however this ...h6 move may prove to be a bit slow in many cases! } ) 8.Bg5 Nbd7 $1 ( 8...Be6 $5 { Of course this natural move is also playable and good } ) 9.a4 $1 h6 ( { Not } 9...b6 $2 { White takes over the light squares in the centre here. } 10.Nd2 Bb7 11.Bc4 $16 ( 11.Nc4 Qc7 12.Ne3 $16 ) ) 10.Be3 ( 10.Bh4 g5 11.Bg3 Nc5 { This is the option Black gets when the knight is on f3 instead of b3. } 12.Nd2 Be6 $132 ) 10...Qc7 ( 10...Ng4 $5 11.Bc1 Ngf6 $1 $11 { intending ...Nc5 } ) 11.O-O Nc5 12.Nd2 Be6 $132 ) ( 7.Nf5 $2 d5 $15 8.Bg5 d4 9.Bxf6 ( 9.Nd5 $4 Bxf5 $19 ) 9...gxf6 10.Nb1 Nc6 $15 ) 7...Be7 $1 { The best move. } ( { One may investigate by himself the move } 7...Be6 { that used to be played by Robert Fischer. } ) 8.O-O ( 8.f4 $6 Nbd7 { gives Black a great game, in which he will develop his bishop to b7 after ...b5 } ) ( 8.Bg5 $5 { Another interesting positional line! } 8...Be6 $1 ( 8...Nbd7 $2 9.a4 $16 { REMEMBER!... THIS POSITION IS PLAYABLE FOR BLACK WITH THE WHITE KNIGHT ON f3 AND NOT ON b3!!, so that we can continue with 1...h6 2.Bh4 g5! 3.Bg3 Nc5! } ) 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.Qd3 ( 10.Nd5 Nd7 11.O-O O-O 12.c3 ( 12.Nxf6+ $2 Nxf6 13.Bf3 Qc7 ( 13...Qb6 $15 ) 14.Re1 Rfd8 $17 ( 14...Rac8 $17 15.c3 Rfd8 16.Qe2 ) 15.c3 b5 16.Qc2 g6 ) 12...Bg5 13.Qd3 Nb6 $15 ( 13...Rc8 $15 14.Rad1 g6 15.Bf3 Kg7 ) 14.Ne3 Na4 ) 10...Be7 $1 { THE KEY MOVE! PREPARING A FAST ...Nd7-Nf6 or .. .Nb6. } 11.Nd5 Nd7 12.O-O-O $1 ( 12.Nxe7 $6 Kxe7 $3 $15 13.O-O Qb6 14.Rad1 Rac8 15.c3 Rhd8 $15 ) 12...Bxd5 13.Qxd5 Qc7 ( 13...Qb6 $11 ) 14.Kb1 O-O $132 { Black has good counter play and he may continue with ...b5-Nb6 etc. } ) ( 8.Be3 Be6 $1 { When I see Be3, I go ...Be6! } ( 8...O-O $2 9.g4 $3 $16 { Carlsen -Nakamura 1-0 } ) 9.Nd5 ( 9.g4 $6 h6 10.h4 Nc6 11.Rg1 d5 $1 ( 11...Nh7 $1 $132 ) 12.exd5 Nxd5 13.Nxd5 Qxd5 ( 13...Bxd5 $5 14.h5 O-O $132 ) 14.Qxd5 Bxd5 15.O-O-O O-O-O 16.Bb6 Rd7 $132 ) ( 9.O-O Nbd7 { transposes } ) 9...Nbd7 10.Qd3 Bxd5 11.exd5 Rc8 { leads to transpositions. } ) 8...O-O { White has several interesting options here. } 9.Be3 ( 9.f4 $2 Nbd7 10.Be3 b5 $15 ) ( 9.Kh1 $5 { White tries to play a useful little move.. but so do we! } 9...Re8 $5 10.Be3 ( 10.f4 $6 b5 $132 ( 10...Nc6 $5 $132 ) ) 10...Be6 11.f4 exf4 12.Bxf4 Nc6 $11 { with typical play. } ) ( 9.Qd3 { Somewhat similar to 9.Be3, 10.Qd3. } 9...Be6 10.Nd5 Bxd5 11.exd5 Nbd7 12.a4 b6 $1 $132 { Black now has a good way to meet any queenside advance by White. } 13.a5 ( 13.c4 a5 $1 $11 ) 13...b5 $1 $11 ) ( 9.Bf3 $5 Be6 10.a4 Nbd7 { with typical Najdorf play... no theory is needed here. } ) 9...Be6 { We should be able to answer the question: What is Black's plan in case White starts playing inconsequential moves? The general idea is ...Nbd7, . ..Rc8 and ... Nb6-c4 followed by ...Rxc4 after Bxc4. Then we get the bishop pair and can press White on the c-file and play the ...d5 break in some cases. Practice has shown that if Black carries out this plan, he can become better. } ( 9...b5 $2 { This is a premature advance. } 10.a4 $1 { White punishes Black's play by forcing unfavorable exposure of the b-pawn and queenside squares. } 10...b4 11.Nd5 Bb7 ( 11...Nxd5 $2 12.Qxd5 $18 { loses material. } ) ( 11...Nxe4 $2 { loses material after } 12.Bf3 $1 Bf5 13.Nxe7+ Qxe7 14.Qd5 $18 ) 12.Bb6 $16 { After the queen's retreat, White has numerous ways to secure a big advantage. 12.Nb6 is also strong. } ) 10.a4 $5 ( 10.Nd5 Nbd7 $3 { ...Bxd5 is the right idea, but this move, taking advantage of the fact that e4 is hanging, is the most accurate! It forces a concession from White. } 11.f3 $2 { White wants to play c4 next, with a grip over the centre but is not in time. } ( 11.Qd3 $1 { transposes to 10.Qd3 } ) ( 11.Bf3 $6 Nxd5 12.exd5 Bf5 $15 { The computer immediately points out that Black is better. The next move is ...Bg6 intending ...f5 and the f and e pawns can start rolling with tempi. } ) 11...Bxd5 12.exd5 b5 $3 $36 { We counter the c2-c4 idea and the d5-pawn becomes a target for our knights. } 13.a4 Nb6 14.axb5 Nbxd5 15.Bf2 axb5 16.Bxb5 Nf4 $15 { We have traded a flank pawn for a central one and achieved good outposts for our pieces. } ) ( 10.Qd3 $5 { This interesting little system has always been popular, but it's not really dangerous. Black has several ways to play against it! } 10...Nbd7 11.Nd5 $1 Bxd5 ( 11...h6 $2 12.c4 $1 $16 Bxd5 13.cxd5 ) 12.exd5 Rc8 $1 { This is one of the many playable moves here... theory is not so important... understanding of the positions is what matters! BY THE WAY... WE ARE THREATENING 13...Nb6! here!! } ( 12...Nc5 $5 { is an entirely different story! } ) 13.c4 $1 ( 13.f3 $2 Nb6 14.Bxb6 Qxb6+ 15.Kh1 g6 $17 ( 15...Nd7 $17 ) ) ( 13.a4 $2 Nb6 14.Bf3 Nc4 $15 ) 13...Ne8 ( 13...a5 $5 $132 ) ( 13...g6 $5 $132 ) 14.Qd2 ( 14.Rac1 Bg5 $1 ( 14...f5 ) ) ( 14.Bg4 $6 e4 15.Qxe4 Nef6 16.Qd4 Nxg4 17.Qxg4 Ne5 18.Qe2 Nxc4 19.Bd4 Bf6 $15 ) 14...f5 $132 ( 14...b6 $132 ) ) ( 10.f4 $5 { In response to this move we should take followed by ...Nc6. } 10...exf4 11.Bxf4 ( 11.Rxf4 Nc6 12.Nd4 Nxd4 $1 13.Bxd4 { We can follow two paths to get a slight advantage here: } 13...Nd7 $3 $15 { Taking aim at the e5-outpost. } ( 13...d5 $3 $15 { Simplifying, but the position will be a bit more comfortable for Black after central trades. } ) 14.Nd5 Bg5 15.Rf1 Bxd5 16.exd5 Bf6 $1 $15 { We want to trade bishops and achieve a "good knight versus bad bishop" type of position. We have a clear strategic initiative here. } ) 11...Nc6 12.Kh1 d5 ( 12...Ne5 $11 { This is another good path. White achieves nothing by doubling Black's pawns with } 13.Nd4 Qc7 14.Nxe6 $6 fxe6 15.Bxe5 $6 dxe5 $15 { The doubled e-pawns in fact allow Black to control a lot of important squares and they're an asset, not a liability. White was completely outplayed from a similar position in the game Ragios-Kelires included in the database. } ) 13.e5 Ne4 $11 { A concrete way to achieve a good game, liked by the computer a lot. } ( 13...Nd7 { This move was played by Kasparov and is also good. } 14.Nxd5 Ndxe5 15.Nxe7+ Qxe7 $11 { Black keeps a very nice position by utilizing the main strategy of fighting against the bishop pair, namely occupying strong central squares with our pieces. e5 is one such square, for the knights, and d5 will be another, for the bishop. } ) ) ( 10.Kh1 Nbd7 11.f4 $6 ( 11.Qd2 Rc8 12.f4 b5 13.f5 Bc4 ) 11...Rc8 $1 $15 ( 11...b5 $1 $15 12.f5 Bc4 ) 12.f5 Bc4 ) ( 10.Qd2 { similar to 10.a4 } 10...Nbd7 11.f4 $2 ( 11.a4 $1 { transposes to the Karpov system } 11...Rc8 $5 ( 11...Nb6 $5 { This is also playable, but Black doesn't get to recapture with the rook on c4. } 12.a5 Nc4 13.Bxc4 Bxc4 14.Rfd1 h6 $1 $132 ) 12.a5 Qc7 ) 11...b5 $3 $15 { We start our own play on the queenside and achieve the better chances. } ( 11...exf4 { Not inherently wrong, but there are better options than this. } 12.Bxf4 Ne5 13.Nd4 Rc8 14.Kh1 $11 ) ( 11...Rc8 $1 $15 { with similar ideas to 11.. .b5 is also strong: } 12.f5 Bc4 13.Bxc4 Rxc4 14.Qd3 b5 $15 ) 12.a3 ( 12.f5 Bc4 13.g4 $2 { White is not in time with his attack and will only be duly punished for overextension. } ( 13.Bxc4 bxc4 14.Nc1 Qb8 $1 $15 { We hit b2 and also prepare ...Qb7. } ) 13...Bxe2 14.Qxe2 b4 15.Nd5 Nxd5 16.exd5 Bg5 $19 { Black is in full control of both flanks. White is massively overextended, with numerous weak points in his camp. } ) 12...Rc8 $15 { Black is simply more effective with his queenside play than White on the kingside. A potential f5 and g4 can lead to more trouble than good for White. } ( 12...Nb6 { is a good alternative. } 13.fxe5 dxe5 14.Qxd8 Bxd8 $15 { The endgame is at least more pleasant for Black. } ) ) 10...Nbd7 11.Qd2 Rc8 $1 ( 11...Nb6 $1 { A playable line, chosen by Kasparov and Carlsen. Black threatens ...Rc8 and then eventually capturing with the rook on c4!! } 12.a5 $1 { In this way White induces the bishop, not the rook, to c4 after the trade. } 12...Nc4 13.Bxc4 Bxc4 14.Rfd1 h6 $1 $132 { with a playable, unclear position. } ) 12.a5 $1 { This is the so-called Karpov system. A strange position appears where no side has a clear plan other than move the pieces up and down,  looking for a good moment to take the initiative! } 12...Qc7 ( 12...Ng4 $5 { Black doesn't often go for this trade, but it is in fact a playable option. } 13.Bxg4 Bxg4 14.Nc1 Be6 15.Nd3 h6 16.Nb4 Nf6 $132 ) 13.Rfd1 Rfe8 ( 13...Rfd8 $132 ) ( 13...h6 $5 $132 ) 14.h3 h6 15.Qe1 Qc6 16.Bf3 Nh7 $132 { These are sample lines of course! There are countless possibilities for both sides! } 

