 1.e4 $1 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.a4 Be6 ( { Whenever you see a2-a4 in the Najdorf, the idea of } 9...Nc6 { planning ...Nb4, placing the knight very well, should also come to mind. } ) 10.Bf3 Nbd7 ( 10...Nc6 { is not working now because of } 11.Nd5 $1 { Previously this wasn't possible because of the hanging e4-pawn. } 11...Bxd5 12.exd5 { Now the knight becomes misplaced: } 12...Na5 ( 12...Nb4 $2 13.c3 { is not possible. } ) 13.Nd2 $1 $14 { The a5 knight will be a chronic weak link in Black's camp. } ) 11.Re1 ( 11.Nd5 $2 { runs into the plan of kingside pawns' advance: } 11...Nxd5 $1 12.exd5 Bf5 13.c4 Bg6 $1 $15 { planning ...f5, ...e4, ...f4 etc. } ) ( 11.Be3 Rc8 12.Nd5 $4 { is even worse, because White will not be able to advance the c-pawn to c4 easily } 12...Nxd5 13.exd5 Bf5 14.c3 Bg6 $17 { With the familiar kingside pawn avalanche plan. } ) 11...Qc7 { A number of other playable options were possible. In these types of positions, there is a lot of maneuvering and there is usually more than one acceptable path. } ( 11...Nb6 12.a5 Nc4 $11 ) ( 11...Rc8 12.a5 h6 13.Nd2 Rc5 14.Rb1 $13 ) ( 11...Qb8 $5 { A rare, but good idea. } 12.Be3 Bd8 $1 { We want to trade the dark-squared bishops. } 13.a5 b5 14.axb6 Bxb6 15.Bxb6 Qxb6 $11 { A long-term idea of counterplay that guarantees Black equality is ...a5-a4-a3! The game Almasi-Papaioannou illustrates this plan. } ) 12.a5 Rfc8 13.Be3 ( 13.Nd2 b5 14.axb6 Nxb6 15.h3 a5 $11 { Again, look at Almasi-Papioannou for an illustration of this typical plan. } ) 13...h6 { Black stops Bg5 ideas once and for all and introduces the idea of placing his own knight on g5. } ( 13...Nf8 14.Bg5 { can sometimes be annoying. } ) 14.h3 Nf8 ( 14...b5 { was a viable alternative leading to a different type of position: } 15.axb6 Nxb6 16.Nd2 a5 $11 ) 15.Nc1 N8h7 16.Nd3 Ng5 17.Nb4 Bd8 18.Nbd5 Nxf3+ 19.Qxf3 Bxd5 ( 19...Nxd5 $6 20.exd5 Bd7 21.Qg3 $1 $14 { allows White to develop an initiative on the kingside } 21...Kh8 22.f4 $36 ) 20.exd5 { The position is unclear, with chances for both sides, but I managed to prevail. } 20...Qd7 21.Qe2 ( 21.Red1 $2 { allows } 21...Rc4 $1 22.Qe2 Rac8 $17 ) 21...Bc7 $6 ( 21...Qf5 $1 { The excellent f5-square should be occupied by the queen. } ) 22.Qd3 Re8 ( 22...Qd8 { led to dynamic equality: } 23.b4 b5 24.axb6 Bxb6 25.Rxa6 Rxa6 26.Qxa6 Rxc3 27.Bxb6 Qc8 $11 ) 23.Bd2 Rac8 24.Na4 e4 25.Qd4 Qf5 26.c4 Bd8 27.Nc3 $14 Rc7 28.b4 $6 { White was not careful enough to consider Black's hidden possibilities. } 28...Qc8 $3 { The problem is,  the c-pawn now falls and White's advantage evaporates. Black can start pressing a bit and in the game, I managed to outplay my opponent. } 29.Nxe4 Nxe4 30.Rxe4 Bf6 31.Rae1 ( 31.Rxe8+ Qxe8 32.Qb6 Rxc4 33.Re1 Qd7 34.Qe3 Be5 $15 ) 31...Rxe4 32.Qxe4 Rxc4 33.Qe8+ Qxe8 34.Rxe8+ Kh7 35.Rb8 $2 ( 35.Kf1 $1 Rd4 36.Bc3 Rd1+ 37.Re1 Rxd5 38.Bxf6 gxf6 39.Re7 Rb5 40.Rxf7+ Kg6 41.Rd7 d5 $15 ) 35...Rd4 $1 36.Be3 Rxb4 37.Bb6 Bc3 $1 38.Kf1 Rb5 39.Ke2 f6 40.Kd3 Bxa5 41.Bxa5 Rxd5+ 42.Ke4 Rxa5 

