 { Not a perfect game, but an example of Black taking over the position with reasonable play. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Bf3 $5 { A playable move without much theory... just typical ideas... on the other hand, this bishop may prove to be missing from the f1-a6 diagonal... and the a6 pawn will not be under attack in case of a 1. a5-b6 situation! } 9...Be6 10.a4 Nbd7 ( 10...Nc6 $2 { is wrong now: } 11.Nd5 Bxd5 12.exd5 Nb4 13.c3 ) 11.a5 { Of course many many other moves are possible here for White. We should not bother to memorize anything! } ( 11.Be3 ) ( 11.Bd2 ) ( 11.Re1 ) 11...Rc8 ( 11...Qc7 $1 { Black could move the other rook to c8 and carry out the ...b5 break. } 12.Be3 Rfc8 13.Re1 b5 14.axb6 Nxb6 15.Na5 Nc4 16.Nxc4 Bxc4 $132 ) 12.Be3 Qc7 13.Re1 Rfe8 14.Nd2 h6 ( 14...Qc6 $5 ) 15.Nf1 Qc6 16.Ng3 Nf8 17.h3 N8h7 18.h4 Bd8 19.Nf1 Nd7 20.g3 Nhf6 21.Re2 Nc5 22.Nd2 b6 23.axb6 Bxb6 $36 24.Ra3 Red8 25.b4 Ncd7 26.Re1 Bxe3 27.Rxe3 Qb7 28.Qb1 Nb6 29.Na4 Nxa4 30.Rxa4 d5 31.exd5 Bxd5 32.Bxd5 Nxd5 33.Rd3 Nc3 34.Qb3 Rxd3 35.cxd3 Nxa4 36.Qxa4 Rc1+ 37.Nf1 Qb5 38.Qa3 Rd1 39.Qc3 Qxd3 40.Qc8+ Kh7 41.Qh3 Qf3 42.h5 e4 43.Qc8 e3 44.Qc2+ f5 

