 { This game with its annotations shows instances when the ...Nc6-b4 scheme of development works for Black. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Re1 ( 9.a4 Nc6 $5 ( 9...Be6 $1 10.Be3 Nc6 $3 11.Qd2 Nb4 $3 12.Bf3 Rc8 13.Rfd1 ( 13.h3 $2 d5 $17 14.exd5 Nfxd5 15.Nxd5 Nxd5 $17 ( 15...Bxd5 $17 ) ) 13...Ng4 $15 ) 10.Bg5 Be6 11.Bxf6 Bxf6 12.Nd5 Bg5 $11 ) ( 9.Be3 Be6 10.a4 $6 ( 10.Qd2 $1 Nbd7 ( 10...Nc6 $6 11.Bf3 ) 11.a4 ) 10...Nc6 $1 11.Qd2 Nb4 $11 ) 9...Be6 10.a4 ( 10.Bf3 Re8 11.a4 Nc6 $2 12.Nd5 $1 $16 Bxd5 13.exd5 Na5 $6 ( 13...Nb8 14.a5 $1 $16 Nbd7 15.c4 Rc8 16.Be2 g6 17.Be3 ) 14.Nd2 $3 Rc8 15.b3 Qc7 16.c4 $16 ) 10...Nc6 $3 11.Be3 ( 11.Nd5 $2 Nxe4 $19 ) ( 11.Bf3 Nb4 $1 12.a5 Rc8 13.Ra4 ( 13.Be3 Qd7 14.Ra4 $2 Nxc2 $3 15.Qxc2 Qxa4 $19 ) 13...d5 $36 ) 11...Nb4 $1 12.Bf3 Rc8 13.a5 Qd7 14.h3 h6 $2 ( { Black should have struck immediately with } 14...d5 $1 $17 15.exd5 Bf5 $3 16.Rc1 e4 17.Be2 Nbxd5 ) 15.Re2 Bc4 $2 { Now White manages to take control of the position. } ( { Again, the energy of the b4-knight should be directed towards the central break: } 15...d5 $3 $15 ) 16.Rd2 Qe6 17.Ra4 $4 ( { After the collected } 17.Nc1 $16 { Black's queenside pieces would end up badly placed and Black would get in trouble. } ) 17...Nxc2 $1 $19 { A typical tactical motive. Black wins. } 18.Rxc2 Bxb3 19.Rb4 Bd8 20.Bb6 Bxc2 21.Qxc2 Rc4 22.Qa4 Rxb4 23.Qxb4 Bxb6 24.Qxb6 Qd7 25.Kh2 Rc8 26.Qb4 Qc6 27.Nd5 Nxd5 28.exd5 Qc7 29.Qg4 g6 30.Be4 Kg7 31.h4 h5 32.Qh3 Qc1 33.g3 Rc4 34.Bg2 Qxb2 35.Qd7 Qxf2 36.Qxd6 Qe2 37.Qa3 Rc2 38.Qf3 Qxf3 

