 { A cautionary example of how Karpov used to squeeze his opponents in Be2 Najdorf. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 Nf6 4.Nc3 cxd4 5.Nxd4 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Be3 Be6 10.Qd2 Nbd7 11.a4 Rc8 12.a5 Qc7 13.Rfd1 Rfd8 14.Qe1 Qc6 15.Bf3 Bc4 16.Nc1 h6 17.N1a2 Nc5 18.Nb4 Qe8 19.g3 Rc7 20.Bg2 Rdc8 21.b3 Be6 22.Ncd5 Nxd5 23.Nxd5 Bxd5 24.Rxd5 Rc6 25.Rad1 Ne6 26.c4 Bg5 27.Ba7 { Karpov prefers to keep control over the whole position instead of going for the short-term gain of a pawn. } ( 27.Rxd6 Rxd6 28.Rxd6 Bxe3 { gave Black some counterplay. He either gets the d4-square or damages White's pawn structure. } 29.Qxe3 ( 29.fxe3 $6 Rd8 ( 29...Rc6 $5 ) 30.Rxd8 ( 30.Qd2 Rxd6 31.Qxd6 Qd8 32.Qxd8+ Nxd8 33.Bh3 Nc6 34.Bc8 Nxa5 35.b4 Nxc4 36.Bxb7 Nxe3 37.Bxa6 Kf8 $11 ) ( 30.Rd5 $1 Nc7 31.c5 $1 { is still very good for White, but also unbalanced and hard to find. } ) 30...Qxd8 $11 ) 29...Nd4 ) 27...Ra8 28.Bb6 Bd8 29.Be3 Bc7 30.Qe2 b6 ( { If Black sat and waited with } 30...Rc8 { White could further increase his dominance in a number of ways: } 31.h4 $18 ( 31.b4 Bb8 32.Rc1 $18 ) ) 31.b4 bxa5 32.b5 axb5 33.cxb5 Rc5 34.Bxc5 Nxc5 35.Bf1 a4 36.Qc2 a3 37.Bc4 Ne6 38.R5d3 Nd4 39.Qa2 Bb6 40.Rxa3 { An amazing game by Karpov! } 

