 { A great game by Petrosian ...in the Sveshnikov type Najdorf! } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Bg5 Be6 ( 9...Nbd7 $2 { is not satisfactory because White will clamp down on the light squares. } 10.a4 b6 ( 10...h6 11.Bh4 g5 12.Bg3 { This plan works with the knight on f3. But here the b3-knight is ready to take after ...Nc5, e.g. } 12...Qc7 13.f3 Nc5 14.Nxc5 dxc5 15.Bc4 $16 ) 11.Bc4 $1 Bb7 12.Nd2 $1 { With this maneuvre White establishes control over the centre. The knight is ready to head towards d5 in the future. We should not allow this scenario. } 12...Qc7 13.Qe2 $16 ) 10.Bxf6 { Logical, since there was a positional threat of ...Nbd7, after which the bishop does absolutely nothing on g5. } ( 10.a4 $6 Nbd7 { would lead to Karpov system with a number of tempi up for Black: } 11.Be3 Rc8 12.a5 { Apart form the usual ...Qc7, an exchange sacrifice is a serious option here. } 12...Rxc3 $5 ( { After } 12...Qc7 { a sample line includes } 13.Qd2 h6 14.h3 Rfe8 15.Rfd1 Nf8 16.Qe1 N8h7 17.f3 Nf8 $11 { Once f3 has been played, the knight can be redirected toward f4. } ) 13.bxc3 Nxe4 14.c4 Qc7 $44 ) ( 10.f4 exf4 11.Bxf4 Nc6 12.Kh1 Rc8 13.Nd4 Nxd4 14.Qxd4 Qc7 $11 ( { In addition to the typical ... Nd7-e5 plan, there is a so-called Portisch plan, named after the Hungarian grandmaster, available in positions like this: } 14...Ne8 $5 { with the idea of ...Bf6-e5. } ) ) 10...Bxf6 11.Nd5 Nd7 $1 ( 11...Bxd5 $2 { is not satisfactory. } 12.Qxd5 Qc7 13.c3 Be7 { If Black is given one move, he will keep control of d5 with ...Nd7-f6 (b6) . But White has a wonderful positional idea. } 14.Bg4 $1 { White will now take the knight as soon as it appears on d7. } ( 14.Rad1 Nd7 $11 ) 14...Nd7 ( 14...Nc6 15.Rad1 $16 { The knight on c6 does nothing and White firmly controls the key d5-square. } ) 15.Bxd7 Qxd7 16.Rfd1 Rfd8 { The knight now maneuvers to d5. } 17.Na5 Rab8 18.Nc4 Qc6 19.Qd3 $16 { Intending Ne3. White is much better. } ) 12.Qd3 ( 12.Nxf6+ Nxf6 13.Bf3 { A typical course of action in such a position would be } 13...Qc7 ( { We should not play } 13...d5 $2 { in a position like this. The trades would only weaken a number of squares and reduce our potential. } ) ( 13...b5 { is playable. } ) 14.c3 Rfd8 15.Qd2 b5 16.Rfe1 Rac8 17.h3 g6 18.Rad1 Kg7 $15 { Black slowly improves all of his pieces, including the king and keeps White's pieces passive. The ...Nd7-b6 manuvre is possible. We want to advance our pawn with ...a5-b4 and maybe ...d5 at the right moment. } ) ( 12.c3 Bg5 13.Bg4 $2 { and now what??? Look at the solution in the STRATEGICAL EXERCISE file. } ) ( 12.c4 { is different from a typical grip with Be3. Black plays } 12...Bg5 $15 { and White is weak on the dark squares. } ) 12...Rc8 { Threatening to take on d5. } 13.c3 Bg5 $15 { Black gets a good version of the Sveshnikov. } 14.Rad1 ( 14.Qg3 $2 { This move would be a positional crime on account of } 14...Bxd5 $1 15.exd5 f5 $17 { With a favorable structure and a kingside initiative for Black. } ) 14...Kh8 $1 { Black steps away from all the knight checks that can happen in the long run, depriving White of any hidden tactical possibilities once and for all. } 15.Bf3 g6 $1 { Intending ..f5. } 16.Ne3 { In the absence of a real plan, White plays "normal" moves that don't really improve his position. } 16...Rc6 17.Rfe1 Nf6 $1 { Super-positional style by Petrosian. White can no longer enter d5 without consequences. } 18.Qe2 ( 18.Nd5 $2 { is met with the familiar } 18...Bxd5 $1 19.exd5 Rc8 $17 { , e.g. } 20.c4 Nd7 $17 { controlling the dark squares and intending ... f5, with a domination. } ) 18...b5 19.Ra1 Qb6 20.Nd2 ( { In case of } 20.Red1 { Black will take the opportunity to weaken White's structure with } 20...Bxe3 21.Qxe3 Qxe3 22.fxe3 Rd8 { The resulting endgame is strategically lost for White, with a sample line: } 23.Na5 Rc7 24.Kf1 g5 25.g3 g4 26.Bg2 Kg7 $19 ) ( 20.Rad1 a5 21.Nc1 { Although we would keep the pieces on the board, being much more active, theoretically speaking there is nothing wrong with simplifying with } 21...Bxe3 22.Qxe3 Qxe3 23.Rxe3 Rd8 $17 { Intending to put the king on e7 and advance pawns on the queenside, with a big advantage. } ) 20...a5 $17 { You can study the rest of the game by yourself because we have already explained the model way of obtaining a nearly decisive advantage. Black won very convincingly. } 21.Ndf1 Rfc8 22.a3 b4 23.cxb4 axb4 24.a4 Qa7 25.Red1 Ra6 26.Rd3 b3 27.a5 Rcc6 28.Qd1 Qc7 29.Nd5 Bxd5 30.exd5 Rc5 31.Rxb3 Raxa5 32.Rxa5 Rxa5 33.Rc3 Qb6 34.Rb3 Qa7 35.Rb4 Kg7 36.h4 Bh6 37.b3 Ra2 38.Qe1 Qa5 39.Qb1 Ra1 40.Rb5 Qc3 

