 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Be2 Be6 9.O-O Nbd7 $5 { This move order allows black to play for a fast ... Nbd7-Rc8-Nb6 without castling! } 10.a4 Rc8 11.Qd2 { I scared my opponent with the prospect of an exchange sacrifice on c3. } ( { The critical move was } 11.a5 ) 11...Nb6 $1 { Now I get to realize the main idea of ...Nc4 followed by ...Rxc4 or force White to make concessions in order to stop it. } ( 11...O-O 12.a5 { transposes to the Karpov system with sample lines: } 12...Qc7 13.Rfd1 Nc5 $132 ( 13...Rfd8 14.h3 Qc6 15.Bf3 h6 $132 ) ) 12.Na5 { White stops ...Nc4, but his knight becomes misplaced on a5. } 12...Qc7 13.f4 exf4 14.Rxf4 ( 14.Bxf4 $4 Qc5+ $19 { wins the knight. } ) 14...O-O $15 15.Raf1 Nfd7 { Typically occupying the e5-square with a knight. } 16.Kh1 Ne5 17.R4f2 Bh4 { Provoking the g3 weakening. Remember this idea. } 18.g3 Be7 { Black has a big advantage. In the later game White defended well, while I played perhaps too passively to extract the full point. Nevertheless, White had to defend for many moves to make a draw. } ( { According to the computer, the following retreat was even better: } 18...Bd8 $17 { White would find himself in huge trouble because of the ...Nxa4 threat, e. g. } 19.Rd1 Nxa4 $1 20.Nxa4 Qxa5 21.Qxa5 Bxa5 22.Rxd6 Rxc2 $19 ) 19.Qd4 Nbd7 20.Nb3 Rfe8 21.Qd2 Bf8 22.Nd4 Nb6 23.Nxe6 fxe6 24.Qd4 Nbd7 25.Bg5 Qb6 26.Qxb6 Nxb6 27.Kg2 Be7 28.Be3 Nbd7 29.Rd1 Rc6 30.h3 Bf6 31.Bf1 Rec8 32.Nb1 Rxc2 33.Rxd6 Rxf2+ 34.Kxf2 Be7 35.Rd1 Nf6 36.Nc3 Bb4 37.Bd4 Bc5 38.Bxc5 Rxc5 39.Be2 Kf7 40.Ke3 Ke7 41.Kd4 Nfd7 42.Rc1 Rc6 $17 { We see that even at this point, despite suboptimal play, Black is much better. But soon a mistake comes. } 43.b4 Rb6 $2 { This finally allowed White enough play to equalize. } ( 43...Rd6+ $1 { still gave Black winning chances: } 44.Ke3 Nb6 45.a5 Nbc4+ $17 ) 44.Na2 { The c-file is now under White's control. The rook on b6 is awkwardly placed and will need to be exchanged. } 44...g5 ( { After } 44...Nc6+ { White needs some accurate moves but holds equality: } 45.Kc3 e5 ( 45...a5 46.Bb5 $1 $11 ) 46.Bg4 $1 ( 46.a5 $6 Nd4 $1 $17 ) 46...Nf6 47.a5 $1 Rb5 48.Re1 $11 { The rook hits b4, but is otherwise awkward on b5. } ) 45.Ke3 ( 45.Rc8 { would be similar to the game: } 45...Rc6 46.Rxc6 Nxc6+ $11 ) 45...h6 46.Rc8 Rc6 47.Rxc6 Nxc6 48.b5 Ncb8 49.bxa6 bxa6 50.a5 Kf6 { The game is completely drawish now and draw was agreed without playing it out to the end. } 

