 { Let's study this nice game to see typical Najdorf middlegames and endgames!! } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Be3 Be6 10.Nd5 Nbd7 11.Qd3 Bxd5 12.exd5 Nc5 $5 { A risky but playable line. Nigel Short used to dislike the resulting structure for White despite a positive engine evaluation. This fact goes to show that the direction we want to go in our opening choices should not only be decided by blunt engine evaluation but also by common sense. Some positions are very playable for computers, but not so playable for humans. } ( 12...Rc8 $1 { is the main recommendation. } ) 13.Nxc5 dxc5 14.Bf3 ( 14.d6 $11 { is playable, but not dangerous. } ) 14...Bd6 15.Rfe1 Ne8 { Intending ... f5. Black already appears to have a very nice game. } 16.g3 ( 16.Bg4 g6 17.Bh6 Ng7 $132 ) 16...f5 17.Bg2 Qc7 18.c4 e4 19.Qd2 Nf6 ( 19...Be5 20.f3 Nd6 $11 ) 20.Bg5 ( 20.f3 Rae8 21.fxe4 Nxe4 22.Bxe4 ( 22.Qc2 $132 h5 ) 22...Rxe4 23.b3 Bxg3 $17 ) 20...h6 $1 ( 20...Ng4 21.f3 exf3 22.Bxf3 Ne5 23.Be2 Rae8 $132 ) 21.Bxf6 Rxf6 22.f3 Be5 { Black gambits a pawn in return for domination on the dark squares. } ( 22...e3 { was not as good: } 23.Rxe3 f4 24.Re6 fxg3 25.hxg3 $11 ) 23.Kh1 ( 23.f4 Bd6 $17 { is of course very bad for White. } ) 23...Raf8 ( 23...Qd6 { was another option: } 24.fxe4 f4 25.gxf4 Rxf4 26.Bh3 g6 $15 ) 24.fxe4 f4 25.gxf4 Bxf4 ( 25...Rxf4 $2 26.d6 $1 { suddenly gives White counterplay and he can take over the initiative. } 26...Qf7 $1 $11 { with complication that should objectively lead to equality. } ( 26...Qxd6 27.Qxd6 Bxd6 28.e5 $14 ) ( 26...Bxd6 27.e5 Be7 28.Qd5+ Kh8 29.Qxb7 $14 ) ) 26.Qe2 Qe5 ( 26...Be5 $1 $36 { was the best move, and if } 27.Rf1 { then } 27...Bxh2 ) 27.Bh3 g6 $6 ( 27...Bc1 $3 $17 { I missed that. } ) 28.Rf1 Kg7 29.Rad1 h5 30.Rf2 Kh6 31.Rdf1 Bg5 32.Rxf6 Rxf6 33.Rxf6 Bxf6 34.Bc8 Qg5 35.Qf1 Kg7 $15 36.d6 ( 36.Bxb7 $2 { Grabbing pawns is irrelevant because Black builds a mating net in the meantime. } 36...Qd2 37.Bxa6 Be5 38.Qg1 Qe2 $19 ) 36...Qd2 37.d7 Be5 $17 38.Qg2 Qd1+ 39.Qg1 Qd3 40.Bxb7 h4 $4 { I missed a direct win. Still, Black preserves an edge even with this mistake and I still managed to win the game. } ( 40...Bd4 $3 $19 { Forcing resignation!! } 41.Bd5 Qf3+ 42.Qg2 Qd1+ 43.Qg1 Qxg1# ) 41.d8=Q Qxd8 42.Bd5 Qf6 43.Qg2 a5 44.b3 Kh7 $6 45.Bb7 $2 ( 45.Qe2 $1 $15 ) 45...Qf4 46.Bc8 Qc1+ 47.Qg1 Qc2 48.a4 Bd4 49.Qg4 Qf2 50.Qd1 Be5 51.Qg1 Qf3+ 52.Qg2 Qd1+ 53.Qg1 Qxb3 $19 54.Qg4 Qb1+ 55.Kg2 Qc2+ 56.Kf3 Qxh2 $19 57.Bf5 gxf5 58.Qxf5+ Kg7 59.Qd7+ Kf6 60.Qd8+ Ke6 61.Qe8+ Kd6 62.Qd8+ Kc6 63.Qe8+ Kc7 

