 { A fantastic game with the typical Najdorf ideas!! } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Be3 Be6 ( 8...O-O $6 { This is an inaccurate move order because of } 9.g4 $1 Be6 10.g5 Nfd7 11.Qd2 Nc6 12.O-O-O $16 { with a clear initiative for White. See the game Carlsen-Nakamura. } ) 9.Qd3 ( 9.O-O Nbd7 10.Qd2 ( 10.a4 Rc8 11.a5 ) ) ( 9.g4 { can now be met by } 9...d5 ) 9...O-O 10.Nd5 Nbd7 ( 10...Bxd5 11.exd5 Nbd7 $6 { again allows } ( 11...a5 $1 { is still playable. } ) 12.g4 $1 $16 { Be careful about this possibility that comes up if White hasn't castled yet. } ) ( 10...Nxd5 $3 { certainly gives Black a good game: } 11.exd5 Bc8 12.Qd2 Nd7 13.O-O f5 14.f4 Nf6 $11 ) 11.O-O ( { Remember that } 11.c4 { is met by the freeing break: } 11...b5 ) 11...Bxd5 12.exd5 Rc8 { After some intrigues we arrived at the main line of the Qd3-Nd5 system... Black plays very good moves and little by little he gains the upper hand! } 13.c4 Ne8 $1 14.Rac1 ( 14.Bg4 $6 e4 $3 { is also mentioned in the annotation to the Carlsen-Grischuk game. } ( { Incidentally, } 14...g6 { is also playable, e.g. } 15.Bxd7 Qxd7 16.Na5 ( 16.f4 $11 ) 16...Ng7 17.b4 Nf5 $132 ( 17...f5 18.f3 $14 ) ) 15.Qxe4 Nef6 16.Qd4 Nxg4 17.Qxg4 Ne5 18.Qe2 Nxc4 19.Bd4 Bf6 $15 { White is slightly worse. In case he trades the bishops, speeding up Black's queen development, he can already get in big trouble: } 20.Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 21.Rac1 Qxb2 ( 21...b5 $17 ) 22.Qxb2 Nxb2 23.Na5 b5 24.Nc6 Kh8 $17 ) 14...b6 $6 { This move allows White a good option. } ( 14...Bg5 $1 $132 ) ( { or } 14...f5 $1 15.f4 g6 16.Kh1 b6 $132 { were better choices. } ) 15.Kh1 $6 { An unimpressive move. } ( 15.Bg4 $1 { gave White an initiative: } 15...Rb8 16.Bxd7 Qxd7 17.f4 $14 ) 15...Bg5 16.Qd2 Bxe3 17.Qxe3 a5 $1 $15 { Black is doing very well, controlling the dark squares and soon starting the typical kingside expansion. } 18.Nd2 ( 18.Na1 { Getting the knight to b5 would still not achieve much, e.g } 18...f5 19.Nc2 Nc5 20.Na3 Nf6 21.Nb5 Qd7 22.b3 f4 23.Qd2 g5 $17 ) 18...f5 19.b3 Nef6 20.a3 Kh8 21.f4 ( { After } 21.b4 { Black doesn't give White the a-file, but plays } 21...Qe7 $15 ) 21...Re8 22.Nf3 $4 { A blunder. } 22...exf4 23.Qd2 Nc5 $2 ( 23...Re3 $1 $19 { would decide the game convincingly. Still, Black retains some advantage in the game and later manages to win. } ) 24.Nd4 Qe7 25.b4 axb4 26.axb4 Nb3 27.Nxb3 Qxe2 28.Qxf4 Qe3 29.Qxe3 Rxe3 30.Nd4 g6 31.Nc6 Ne4 32.Rf3 Re2 33.Ra3 Re8 34.h3 Nd2 35.c5 bxc5 36.bxc5 Re1+ 37.Rxe1 Rxe1+ 38.Kh2 f4 39.h4 Nf1+ 40.Kh3 Ne3 41.Rxe3 Rxe3+ 42.Kg4 Rd3 43.cxd6 Rxd5 44.Kxf4 Rxd6 45.Ne5 Rd4+ 46.Kg3 Kg7 47.Nf3 Ra4 48.Kh3 Kf6 49.Ng5 { Donchev-Papaioannou } 49...h6 50.Nf3 Kf5 51.Kg3 Ra3 52.Kh3 Kf4 

