 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 ( { The game quickly reaches a position that could arise starting with } 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 { But if White starts with 6.Be2, he is not obliged to put a bishop on e3 so early. } ) 6...e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.Be2 Nbd7 $5 { A cunning move order ..playing for a very fast ...Nbd7-Rc8-Nb6-Nc4! } 9.a4 ( { After } 9.O-O Rc8 10.f4 ( 10.Qd2 Be7 { We will be in time to play ...Nb6 anyway, so we should develop. At any time now we meet a2-a4 with ...Nb6 before White achieves a4-a5. } 11.a4 ( 11.Rfd1 O-O 12.a4 Nb6 $11 { and now } 13.Na5 $6 { fails to achieve anything: } 13...Qc7 $15 ) 11...Nb6 $11 ) { we can simply play } 10...Be7 { , because our rook is already controlling c4 in anticipation of f4-f5. } 11.f5 Bc4 ) 9...Rc8 10.Qd2 ( { In the case of } 10.a5 { White was scared of the possibility of } 10...Rxc3 $5 $13 { Still, it's not obligatory. Black can also simply play 10...Be7 } ) 10...Nb6 $1 11.O-O Be7 $1 { SOS !! A VERY INSTRUCTIVE MOVE FOR THE AMATEUR PLAYERS! DO NOT FORGET TO DEVELOP YOUR PIECES! ...Nc4 ISN'T GOING ANYWHERE! } 12.Rfd1 Nc4 ( { I think Black should start with } 12...O-O $5 { But Karjakin's move is also good. } ) 13.Bxc4 Rxc4 $1 14.f3 O-O { Black's plan is to triple the major pieces on the c-file. } 15.a5 $6 ( 15.Bg5 $2 { I believe Karjakin knew the refutation of this move: } 15...Ng4 $3 { You may want to memorize this line. } 16.Bxe7 Qb6+ 17.Kf1 Rxc3 $3 18.bxc3 ( 18.Nd4 Rxc2 $3 $19 ) 18...Bc4+ 19.Ke1 Qg1# ) 15...Qc8 $3 $15 { The typical move that is more accurate than ...Qc7 !!! } ( { After } 15...Qc7 16.Nc1 { The idea analogous to the game fails due to tactical reasons: } 16...d5 $2 17.exd5 Nxd5 ( 17...Rd8 18.Bb6 $1 Bc5+ 19.Kh1 Bxb6 20.axb6 Qc8 ( 20...Qxb6 $2 21.Qe2 $1 $18 ) 21.Nd3 $16 ) 18.Nxd5 Bxd5 19.Qxd5 Rd8 20.Qxd8+ $3 Bxd8 21.Bb6 $18 ) 16.Nc1 $6 d5 $1 $17 { In this structure Black should keep the idea of this break in mind. Here it brings Black a fantastic position, opening up his strong bishops. } 17.exd5 Nxd5 18.Nxd5 Bxd5 19.c3 ( 19.Qxd5 $2 Rd8 $19 { is the tactical justification. } ) 19...Bc6 { Other tries were possible, but we can focus on the game continuation. } ( 19...e4 ) ( 19...Be6 $15 ) 20.Nd3 Qf5 21.Nf2 Rh4 $5 $17 { No doubt Karjakin had looked at similar positions with engines and discovered that the h-file invasion with major pieces is the recommended course of action in several instances. } 22.Qe2 Qh5 $1 23.h3 e4 $1 { White's position is completely crushed at this point. } 24.Bd4 Bd8 25.Ng4 exf3 26.Qe5 Qg6 27.Qg3 Rh5 28.Bb6 Bxb6+ 29.axb6 f5 30.Rd6 Qg5 31.Rxc6 fxg4 32.Rc4 gxh3 33.Qxg5 Rxg5 { Study this game several times... preferably, learn it by heart!!! } 

