 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Qd3 Be6 10.Bd2 $5 { A sub-system similar to the the Be3-Qd3-Nd5 line. } 10...Nbd7 11.Nd5 Bxd5 12.exd5 Nc5 $5 { The risky strategy... allowing a passed pawn and blocking it! } ( 12...b6 $5 { is the more restrained strategy, where Black could avoid the risk he faced in the game. } 13.a4 { The position is no-forcing, so there are a number of options. Let's focus on } 13...Re8 $1 ( 13...Qc7 $1 ) ( 13...g6 $1 ) ( { Remember not to allow access to the weak light-squares to the White bishop with the move } 13...a5 $4 { This move recommended after c2-c4, but not before c2-c4! } 14.Rad1 Rc8 15.Be3 Qc7 16.c3 Rfe8 17.Qc2 g6 18.Bb5 $16 ) 14.a5 $6 ( 14.c4 a5 $1 $11 { Now White's bishop is blocked from access to b5 and c6. It will be very hard for White to start a productive plan, while we can proceed with our kingside play. } ) 14...b5 15.c4 bxc4 16.Qxc4 { In a similar scenario we should remember the possibility of improving our queen's position via b8. } 16...Qb8 $3 17.Be3 Qb7 $36 ) 13.Nxc5 dxc5 14.c4 Bd6 15.Qh3 $1 { Compared to the same variation with the bishop on e3, White now has this idea of transferring his forces to the kingside aggressively. } 15...e4 16.f4 exf3 17.Rxf3 Qd7 18.Qh4 Be5 19.Rh3 $2 ( 19.Bd3 $1 $36 { was much more accurate. Black could have faced problems. } ) 19...Rfe8 20.Bd3 h5 21.Bc3 Bxc3 22.bxc3 Re5 23.Rf1 Qe7 24.Qf4 Re8 25.Rg3 Re1 26.Rxg7+ Kxg7 27.Qg5+ Kf8 28.Qh6+ 

