 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Be3 Be6 9.Qd3 Nbd7 10.Nd5 O-O 11.O-O Bxd5 12.exd5 Rc8 13.c4 Ne8 14.Qd2 ( { It may seem that White has an annoying move in the form of } 14.Bg4 { , but Black has a concrete counter-idea. } 14...e4 $1 15.Qxe4 { If White doesn't take, we play ...f5. } 15...Nef6 16.Qf4 Nxg4 17.Qxg4 Ne5 $15 { Black will take on c4 followed by ...Bf6 with a slight edge. } ) 14...b6 15.Rac1 ( 15.f4 f5 16.fxe5 $2 { is not a recommended structure change for White: } 16...dxe5 17.Rac1 a5 18.a4 Nc5 19.Bxc5 Bxc5+ 20.Nxc5 bxc5 $17 { Black has a fantastic d6 square for his knight and the familiar kingside initiative, in addition to some b-file possibilities. } ) 15...a5 16.Na1 g6 17.b4 ( 17.Nc2 Ng7 $132 { allows Black to challenge the Be3 with the ...Nf5 idea. The same idea happens in the game. } ) 17...Ng7 18.bxa5 bxa5 19.Bd3 Nc5 20.Bc2 a4 21.Rb1 e4 22.Bxc5 Rxc5 23.Bxa4 Rxc4 24.Bc6 Nf5 25.Qe2 Rc3 26.Qxe4 Ra3 27.Qe2 Bf6 28.Nb3 Qe7 29.Qxe7 Nxe7 { White was gradually outplayed in this endgame that is intitially much closer to a draw. A rare situation for Carlsen, it is usually him who inflicts such defeats! } 30.Nd2 Rxa2 31.Nc4 Rd8 32.g4 Bd4 33.Rbd1 Bc5 34.Rd2 Rxd2 35.Nxd2 Nxc6 36.dxc6 Rc8 37.Ne4 Rxc6 38.Rd1 h6 39.h4 Kf8 40.Kg2 Ke7 41.Rc1 Rc8 42.Kf3 Ke6 43.Rc2 Rc7 44.h5 gxh5 45.gxh5 Bb6 46.Re2 Bd4 47.Kg3 d5 48.Nd2+ Kf5 49.Kg2 Be5 50.Nf3 Bf6 51.Ra2 Rd7 52.Ne1 Rc7 53.Kf3 Bg5 54.Ra5 Ke5 55.Ke2 Ke4 56.Ra4+ d4 57.f3+ Kd5 58.Ra5+ Kc4 59.Nd3 Re7+ 60.Re5 Re6 61.f4 Bf6 62.Rxe6 fxe6 63.Nf2 Be7 64.Ng4 Kc3 65.f5 exf5 66.Nxh6 Kc2 

