 { This was a balanced game right from the start... Black had good counterplay with the typical ...a5-a4-a3 threat all the time! } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.a4 Be6 ( 9...Nc6 { can be met by } 10.Bg5 $1 ( 10.Bf3 Nb4 { is the idea. } ) 10...Nb4 11.a5 Be6 12.Bxf6 Bxf6 13.Ra4 $1 $14 { The problem is that the knight is forced back. } 13...Nc6 14.Nd5 $14 { with a positional advantage for White. } ) 10.Bf3 Nbd7 11.a5 ( 11.Nd5 $6 { does not work well for White. } 11...Nxd5 $1 12.exd5 Bf5 13.Bd2 Rc8 $1 { Black stops c2-c4. } 14.c3 Bg6 { And now the kingside pawns will advance, with advantage. } 15.Re1 f5 $15 ) 11...Qc7 $5 { It makes sense to keep the rook on a8 and go for a fast b7-b5 since the white light-squared bishop has left the f1-a6 diagonal. } 12.Re1 Rfc8 13.Nd2 b5 $5 14.axb6 Nxb6 15.Nf1 a5 $1 $132 16.Ne3 g6 17.Bd2 ( 17.Ncd5 $2 { would have been bad: } 17...Nfxd5 18.exd5 ( 18.Nxd5 $2 Bxd5 19.exd5 Qxc2 $19 ) 18...Bd7 $17 { We will play ...f5 soon. } ) 17...a4 $1 { The idea of ...a3 is lurking all the time. We played back and forth now without progress for any side, finally agreeing on a draw. } 18.Qe2 h5 19.g3 Qb8 20.Reb1 Kg7 21.h4 Qc7 22.Kg2 Qd7 23.b3 axb3 24.Rxa8 Rxa8 25.cxb3 Ra3 26.b4 Kh7 27.Kg1 

