 { [%evp 0,18,25,38,48,48,64,46,46,18,42,32,54,19,14,0,0,0,0,0,34] In this lecture, we will see the Fianchetto Variation against Najdorf. The starting position arises after the moves: } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 { Again, I prefer this approach. White has three moves that deserve serious attention. } 7.Nde2 ( 7.Nf3 { Is not the most popular move, but it was tried by a few strong players recently. } 7...Be7 { Black has an excellent position after this natural move. Probably the only thing you need to remember here is that: } 8.Nh4 { is well met by } 8...Bg4 $1 { trying to disrupt White's development } ) ( 7.Nb3 { This move reminds the 6.Be2 system. So I recommend to meet it similarly: Be7,Be6,Nbd7,0-0 followed by standart counterplay on the semi-open c-file } ) 7...Be7 8.Bg2 O-O { is the main move, but also 8...h5 deserves attention } 9.O-O { Here I recommend the quick } 9...b5 { Planning to develop the bishop on b7. Black is doing fine in this line } 

