 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 { Quite an interesting positional system for white! However, we can avoid lots of theory with a very nice pet line for black! } 6...e5 { We go for the classical Najdorf with ...e5 instead of the ...e6 setup. } 7.Nb3 ( 7.Nde2 $5 { This is also playable for White... but harmless. } 7...Be7 8.Bg2 O-O $1 ( 8...h5 $5 { This is also interesting. } 9.h3 b5 10.Nd5 ( 10.O-O $6 Nbd7 $1 $36 ) 10...Nbd7 11.Nec3 Bb7 12.O-O Nxd5 13.Nxd5 h4 14.g4 Bxd5 ( 14...O-O $132 ) 15.Qxd5 ( 15.exd5 $2 Bg5 $15 ) 15...O-O 16.Be3 Nb6 $132 ) 9.O-O b5 10.Nd5 $1 ( 10.a4 $6 b4 11.Nd5 Nxd5 12.Qxd5 Ra7 13.Be3 Be6 14.Qd3 Ra8 $1 $132 ) ( 10.h3 $6 Nbd7 11.Be3 Bb7 $36 12.g4 g6 ) 10...Nbd7 11.Nec3 Nxd5 $1 { This is the simplest. } 12.Nxd5 Nf6 13.Nxf6+ ( 13.Nxe7+ Qxe7 14.Be3 Be6 $15 ) 13...Bxf6 { Black is perfectly fine. .. for example } 14.Qd3 ( 14.a4 bxa4 15.Rxa4 a5 $132 16.Bd2 Bd7 17.Ra1 Qc7 $132 ) 14...Be6 15.Rd1 Qc7 $1 $132 { We set a little trap here. } 16.Qxd6 $4 ( 16.c3 Be7 17.Be3 Rfb8 $5 18.f4 f6 $132 ) 16...Rad8 17.Qxc7 Rxd1+ 18.Bf1 Bh3 $19 ) ( 7.Nf3 $5 { This is the latest trend... the idea is to play Nh4-Nf5 or sometimes even Nh4-Ng2-Ne3. } 7...Be7 8.Nh4 Bg4 $5 { The recommendation is to disrupt White's development with this typical idea and not to hurry with a short castle. } 9.Be2 Be6 10.Bf3 g6 $132 { Stopping Nf5. } 11.O-O h5 12.Ng2 Nbd7 $132 { Black can now meet Ne3 with ...h4 any time, making it hard for White to complete his plan without concessions. } ) 7...Be7 8.Bg2 ( 8.Bg5 $5 Nbd7 9.a4 { Hoping for 9...b6?! 10 Bc4! +/- } 9...Qc7 $1 ( 9...b6 $2 10.Bc4 $3 Bb7 11.Nd2 h6 12.Bxf6 Nxf6 13.O-O O-O 14.Qe2 Qc7 15.Rfd1 $16 ) 10.Bg2 h6 11.Be3 Nb6 $132 12.Nd2 Bg4 $1 { The typical disruptive idea. } 13.Bf3 Be6 $132 ) 8...O-O ( 8...b5 { This is by far the main line... with a lot of theory! } 9.Nd5 ) 9.O-O Be6 10.a4 { White's plan is quite clear: a4-Re1-Nd2-f1-e3. } ( 10.Re1 Nbd7 11.Nd2 $6 { The plan is not good for White without a4, as Black gets too much space with ...b5: } 11...b5 $15 12.Nf1 Nb6 13.Ne3 Rc8 14.Ncd5 Nfxd5 15.Nxd5 ( 15.exd5 Bd7 $17 { with ...f5 coming. } ) 15...Bxd5 16.exd5 Bg5 17.Bxg5 ( 17.f4 $2 { weakens White's position decisively: } 17...exf4 18.gxf4 Bf6 $19 ) 17...Qxg5 $17 { Black has the queenside initiative and White lacks activity in return. } ) 10...Nbd7 ( 10...Nc6 $2 { is mistaken, but only because of } 11.Nd5 $1 { If White plays any other move, 11...Nb4 gives Black good play. } 11...Bxd5 12.exd5 Na5 ( 12...Nb4 $2 13.c3 $1 ) ( 12...Nb8 $16 { is sad. } ) 13.Nd2 $16 { with a very bad knight on a5. } ) 11.Re1 ( 11.Be3 Nb6 12.Nd2 { Remember that this piece construction allows us to harass White's dark-squared bishop. } ( 12.Na5 Qc7 $11 ) 12...Ng4 $36 13.Re1 Rc8 14.h3 Nxe3 15.Rxe3 g6 $15 ) 11...Qc7 $1 { The idea is ...Bd8!!, ...Qc6/c5 and ...Bb6 or ...Ba5. Black has a great game! } ( 11...Qb8 $1 { This is also very good! } 12.Nd2 Bd8 13.a5 ( 13.Nf1 Ba5 14.Bd2 Qc7 15.Ne3 Rac8 $132 ) 13...b5 $1 14.axb6 Bxb6 $132 { Black as very nice counterplay. } ) 12.Nd2 ( 12.Be3 Ng4 $11 { and it's hard to find something better than moving the bishop back for White. } ) ( 12.h3 Rfc8 13.a5 b5 14.axb6 Nxb6 $13 { with the idea of pushing the a-pawn later. } ) 12...Qc5 $1 13.Nf1 ( { If } 13.Nb3 { we can either repeat the position or continue an unclear game with ...Qc6. } 13...Qc7 $11 ( 13...Qc6 $5 14.Nd5 Bd8 15.c3 ( 15.h3 Nb6 $15 ) 15...Bg4 16.Qd3 Nxd5 17.exd5 Qc7 $132 ) ) 13...Bd8 $3 { The idea is either ...Bb6 or ...Ba5! Very simple and good! } 14.Be3 { Suddenly the ideas of ...Bb6 and ... Ba5 convince White to put the bishop, and not the knight, as he intended, on e3. It can be considered a success for Black. } ( 14.Ne3 Ba5 $1 ( 14...Bb6 $1 $132 ) 15.Bd2 Rac8 $1 16.Ne2 $2 ( 16.Ncd5 Bxd5 17.exd5 Bxd2 18.Qxd2 g6 $1 $132 ) 16...Ng4 $3 ( 16...Bxd2 17.Qxd2 Ng4 18.Nxg4 Bxg4 19.Rac1 b5 20.b4 Qc6 21.axb5 axb5 22.h3 Be6 23.Red1 Qc4 24.Qe1 Nf6 25.Rxd6 Nxe4 26.Rd3 Nf6 27.Re3 Bd5 28.Rxe5 Bxg2 29.Kxg2 Rfe8 30.Nf4 Rxe5 31.Qxe5 Qxb4 32.Nd5 Nxd5 33.Qxd5 g6 34.c3 Qc4 35.Qxc4 Rxc4 36.Rb1 Rxc3 37.Rxb5 { 1/2-1/2 Wei Yi-Anish Giri 2016 } ) 17.Nxg4 Bxg4 18.Bxa5 Qxa5 19.c3 Qb6 20.Qd2 a5 $1 $15 ) ( 14.Nd5 $6 Nxd5 15.exd5 Bf5 16.Ne3 Bg6 17.b3 ( 17.c3 f5 $17 ) 17...Bb6 18.Ba3 Qc7 $36 ) ( 14.Bd2 Ba5 ( 14...Bb6 $5 $132 ) 15.Ne3 Rac8 $1 { transposes } ) 14...Qb4 $1 ( 14...Qc6 15.Nd5 Bg4 $132 ) 15.Bd2 ( 15.Rb1 Nb6 $3 $36 { We force White to give up his bishop. } ( 15...Ba5 $5 $132 ) 16.Bxb6 Bxb6 17.Ne3 Bxe3 { Not obligatory, but it simplifies to a favourable position. } 18.Rxe3 Rac8 19.Rd3 Rfd8 $15 { Black has the initative. White lacks an active plan. } ) ( 15.Qb1 Ba5 $5 ( 15...Bb6 $6 { is inaccurate: } 16.a5 $5 $14 ) ( 15...Ng4 $5 16.a5 Nxe3 17.Nxe3 Bxa5 $11 { White can get some compensation with } 18.Rd1 ) 16.Bd2 Qc5 17.Be3 Qc7 $11 { We have a very nice game with pressure against White's position and a passive white queen. } ) 15...Qxb2 $15 16.Rb1 Qa3 17.Re3 ( 17.Rxb7 { White regains the pawn, but Black has a choice of moves that give him an edge thanks to White's weaknesses. } 17...Ba5 $17 ( 17...Rc8 $17 ) ( 17...Nb6 $17 ) ) 17...Qc5 18.Rd3 ( 18.Rxb7 Bb6 19.Nd5 Bxd5 20.exd5 Qc8 $19 ) 18...Qc6 19.Nd5 Nc5 20.Nxf6+ Bxf6 21.Rc3 Qxa4 22.Be3 Nxe4 23.Rc7 d5 24.Ra1 Qb4 25.Nd2 Nxd2 26.Bxd2 Qd6 27.Rxb7 Qc6 28.Rb4 e4 29.c3 a5 30.Rba4 Qc7 31.Rc1 Bd7 32.Ra2 Bb5 33.Bf1 Bxf1 34.Qxf1 Rfc8 35.Qb5 Qc5 36.Qd7 Rc7 37.Qf5 Qc4 38.Rca1 a4 39.Bf4 Rca7 40.Be5 Bxe5 41.Qxe5 h6 42.Ra3 Rb7 43.h4 Rb3 44.Rxa4 Rxa4 45.Qe8+ Kh7 46.Rxa4 Rb1+ 47.Kh2 Qf1 { '0-1 Valls Marti, A-Tsolakidou,S/ Barcelona ESP 2017' } 

