 { An interesting game where both players were following the ideas of some super GMs. Finally... balance was kept! } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nde2 Be7 8.Bg2 b5 9.Nd5 Nbd7 10.Nec3 O-O ( 10...Nxd5 $5 11.Nxd5 Nf6 $132 { would have been more simple... } ) 11.a4 bxa4 12.Rxa4 Bb7 13.O-O ( 13.Ra2 $3 $14 { would have prevented the game continuation and would have given White a slight edge. } ) 13...Nxd5 14.Nxd5 Bxd5 $1 { Using the fact that White cannot take with the queen. } 15.exd5 Bg5 16.Bxg5 Qxg5 17.Qe2 ( { In the case of } 17.Qa1 Nc5 18.Ra5 { Black can simply stop b2-b4: } 18...Rfb8 19.b3 Rb4 $11 ) 17...Nc5 18.Rg4 ( 18.Ra3 { Again, Black should stop b2-b4 and preferably occupy the b4 square with his rook. } 18...Rfb8 19.b3 Rb4 20.Rfa1 Rab8 $11 ) 18...Qd8 19.b4 Nd7 20.Ra1 ( 20.Rc4 $5 { was a strong idea connected with a possible exchange sacrifice: } 20...a5 21.b5 Nc5 22.Rxc5 $1 dxc5 23.Qxe5 Re8 24.Qf4 $14 ) 20...a5 $1 21.bxa5 { White plays for an interesting tactical exchange sacrifice. } ( { Of course, } 21.b5 $2 { is totally wrong and gives Black an initiative on both flanks: } 21...Nb6 22.Qd2 f5 23.Rh4 a4 $17 ) 21...Rxa5 22.Rxa5 Qxa5 23.Rxg7+ $1 { This was White's idea all along. } 23...Kxg7 24.Qg4+ Kf6 ( 24...Kh8 { I didn't really like that. .. } 25.Qxd7 Qd8 26.Qf5 Qe7 27.Be4 f6 28.h4 { Black has no way to disentangle his pieces. But it's hard for White to make progress as well. } 28...Rf7 29.Qc8+ ( 29.Kg2 $2 Qd7 $1 $17 ) 29...Qf8 30.Qf5 $11 ) 25.Qh4+ { White has to keep things realistic and satisfy himself with half a point. } ( 25.Qxd7 $2 { does not give White sufficient play at all: } 25...Qb4 $1 26.c3 Qxc3 27.Qxd6+ Kg7 28.h3 h6 29.Qe7 Ra8 $17 { The d-pawn has no time to march because of threats against the white king. } ) 25...Kg7 26.Qg4+ Kf6 27.Qh4+ Kg7 

