 { Regardless of concrete theory and specific analyses, this is a very instructive game for learning the typical ideas of this line. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nde2 Be7 8.Bg2 O-O 9.O-O Be6 { This is a normal move... although 9...b5 is simpler. } ( 9...b5 10.a4 b4 11.Nd5 Nxd5 12.Qxd5 Ra7 13.Be3 Be6 14.Qd2 ( 14.Qd3 Ra8 $1 $11 ) 14...Rb7 $11 ) 10.a4 $1 ( 10.h3 b5 11.a4 b4 12.Nd5 Nxd5 13.exd5 Bf5 $11 { is very good for Black. } ) 10...Nbd7 11.h3 Re8 12.b3 ( { After } 12.g4 { Black can direct his knight toward the weakened h4 and f4 squares with } 12...Nf8 $132 ) 12...Qc7 ( { or } 12...Rc8 ) 13.Be3 ( { or } 13.Bb2 Rac8 ) 13...Rac8 14.Ra2 { White prepares Nd5, but it turns out not to be a good plan. } ( 14.a5 $132 { was more to the point. } ) 14...Nc5 15.Nd5 $6 Nxd5 16.exd5 Bf5 17.g4 $6 Bg6 18.Ng3 Qd8 $1 { It is quite clear that as a result of White's operations, his position has become overextended. } 19.a5 ( 19.Bxc5 $2 { The e4-square is not enough to compensate for the catastrophically weakened dark squares. } 19...Rxc5 20.Ne4 ( 20.Be4 Rc3 21.Bxg6 hxg6 22.Kg2 Bh4 23.Ne4 Rc7 $17 ) 20...Bxe4 21.Bxe4 Rc3 $17 ) 19...Bh4 ( 19...Bg5 { was also sensible: } 20.Qd2 Bxe3 21.Qxe3 Qh4 $11 ) 20.Qe2 h6 21.Rd1 Qe7 22.Bxc5 $2 { White goes for the wrong idea that was mentioned in the comment to the 19th move. } 22...Rxc5 $15 23.c4 e4 $17 24.Nf1 f5 $1 ( 24...Qc7 $5 25.Qe1 b6 { offered White an unexpected counterplay resource: } 26.Re2 $3 $132 ) 25.gxf5 Bxf5 26.Ne3 Bd7 $5 ( 26...Bg6 $17 ) 27.Qh5 Rf8 $1 28.Qg6 Rf4 $2 ( 28...Rxa5 $3 { was an incredibly strong resource with complex tactics as justification. } 29.Rxa5 Bxf2+ 30.Kh1 Bxe3 31.Bxe4 ( 31.Qxe4 Qg5 $19 ) 31...Rf2 32.Qh7+ Kf8 33.Rg1 Qe5 $1 $19 34.Qh8+ Kf7 35.Bg6+ Ke7 ) 29.Rd4 Qf6 $2 { The queen trade changes the evaluation in White's favour because his queenside majority becomes a big asset in the absence of threats against White's king. } 30.Qxf6 Bxf6 31.Rxe4 Rxe4 32.Bxe4 Bxh3 33.b4 Rc8 34.Kh2 $6 { After this cooperative move Black is able to hold the balance comfortably. } ( 34.Rc2 $16 { preparing c4-c5, kept the pressure. } ) 34...Bd7 35.Rc2 Re8 36.f3 Bg5 37.Rc3 Bf6 ( { Incidentally, Black could start playing for the win at the end with } 37...Rc8 $1 38.c5 ( 38.Nf5 g6 $1 $17 ) 38...dxc5 39.bxc5 Bxe3 40.Rxe3 Rxc5 41.d6 Rxa5 42.Bxb7 Ra2+ 43.Kg3 Rd2 44.Bxa6 Rxd6 $15 { The endgame should be drawn, but Black can still press a bit. } ) 38.Rc2 Bg5 39.Rc3 Bf6 40.Rc2 Bg5 

