 { A perfect game by Black. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Bg2 b5 { I suggest 8...0-0 followed by ...Be6, ...Nbd7, . ..Qc7 or ...Qb8 etc. ...but still, knowing the typical plans of this line is really useful and effective! } ( { If } 8...Nbd7 { White should stop ...b5 with } 9.a4 $1 ) 9.O-O ( { My golden rule is that White should not allow both ...b5 and .. .Nbd7 without undermining Black's position, therefore I would prefer } 9.a4 { with White, similar to Hou-Grischuk. } ) 9...Nbd7 10.Bd2 O-O 11.a4 $6 ( 11.Re1 Nb6 12.Na5 ( 12.a3 { Remember the typical disruptive idea: } 12...Bg4 { and either the pawn or the bishop become misplaced: } 13.Bf3 ( 13.f3 Be6 $17 ) 13...Be6 $15 { Black is clearly better. } ) 12...Qc7 $11 { The knight on a5 will be hanging in many possible lines. } ) ( 11.h3 Nb6 $15 { A 12.g4? expansion is only welcome for us in a position like this. White's pawns are on the other side of the board and he will not create an attack with pawns only. The far-advanced pawns will become long-term weaknesses. } ( { Note that ...b4 with the pawn still on a2 allows an eventual a2-a3 undermining of Black's queenside pawns. Therefore I would not go for the following line: } 11...b4 12.Nd5 Nxd5 13.exd5 a5 14.a3 ) ) 11...b4 12.Nd5 Nxd5 13.exd5 a5 14.c3 bxc3 15.Bxc3 Qb6 16.Ra3 f5 $15 17.Re1 $6 ( 17.Qd2 Bd8 $1 { This maneuver is the whole problem and the reason White's plan is not effective. } 18.Rc1 Bb7 19.Kh1 Qa7 20.f4 Bb6 $15 ) 17...Bd8 $17 { The a5-pawn is firmly defended and the bishop will find an excellent position on b6. } 18.Nd2 Ba6 19.Nb3 ( 19.Bf1 Bxf1 20.Rxf1 Qc5 21.Nb3 Qc4 22.Qd2 Nf6 23.Rd1 Ne4 $17 ) 19...Bb7 20.Nd2 Rc8 21.Nb3 Qa7 22.Qd2 Ra8 ( { An immediate attack was also very strong: } 22...f4 $17 { , giving up a5. But Black doesn't even need to sacrifice any material. } ) 23.Nc1 ( 23.Kh1 Nf6 24.f4 e4 25.Nd4 Nxd5 26.Ne6 Rf7 $17 ) 23...Nf6 24.b4 Ne4 $19 { White is completely overwhelmed. } 25.Bxe4 fxe4 26.bxa5 ( 26.Re2 Rc8 27.bxa5 Ba6 28.Rxe4 Bg5 $19 ) ( 26.Rxe4 Bg5 $1 $19 { is the point. } ) 26...Bg5 27.Qa2 ( 27.Qe2 Rac8 28.Na2 Bxd5 29.Bb4 Bc4 30.Qb2 Bd3 31.Bxd6 Rc2 $19 ) 27...e3 28.f3 ( 28.Nd3 Ba6 $19 ) 28...e2+ 29.Kg2 Rxf3 $1 30.Rxe2 ( 30.Kxf3 Qe3+ 31.Kg2 Qe4+ 32.Kh3 Bc8+ $19 ) 30...Bxc1 31.Kxf3 Bxa3 ( 31...Bxa3 32.Qxa3 Bxd5+ 33.Kg4 Qd7+ 34.Kh4 g5+ 35.Kxg5 Qg7+ 36.Kh4 Be6 $19 { A PERFECT GAME BY BLACK } ) 

