 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Bg2 O-O 9.O-O b5 10.a4 ( 10.h3 { Slow play like this will allow Black to place the rook more comfortably on b8 after a2-a4 and Nd5: } 10...Nbd7 11.a4 b4 12.Nd5 Nxd5 13.Qxd5 Rb8 $15 ) 10...b4 11.Nd5 Nxd5 12.Qxd5 ( 12.exd5 a5 $15 { This structure with the key manuvers is explained in the Socko-Karjakin game. } ) 12...Ra7 13.Be3 Be6 14.Qd3 ( 14.Qd2 Rb7 $11 ) 14...Ra8 { If there is a chance (b4 is not hanging) , the rook should go to a8, defending the a-pawn and preparing ... Nd7. } ( { Playing for ...d5 is a totally misguided idea that weakens several squares and hands over the advantage to White: } 14...Rd7 15.Qe2 d5 $2 { The notion that the ...d5 break should be Black's general plan in the Najdorf, which is promoted by a number of sources, is simply misleading. This is a good example. } 16.exd5 Bxd5 17.Bxd5 Rxd5 18.Rfd1 Rxd1+ 19.Rxd1 Qc8 { The position resembles a bad Catalan more than a Najdorf. } 20.Rd5 { White starts attacking Black's weaknesses left and right. } 20...Nc6 21.Nc5 ( 21.Qc4 $16 ) 21...Bxc5 22.Bxc5 $16 ) 15.f4 Qc7 ( { If } 15...f6 { there is an annoying trick: } 16.Bh3 ) 16.Nd2 a5 ( { Black could start with } 16...f6 { , but Grischuk prefers to fix the queenside structure first. } ) 17.Rf2 ( 17.f5 Bc8 $11 { The bishop can be redeployed effectively. } ) 17...f6 18.f5 ( 18.Bh3 Bf7 $132 ) 18...Bf7 19.Rc1 Na6 20.c4 bxc3 ( 20...Nc5 { was also good on account of } 21.Qc2 ( 21.Bxc5 Qxc5 $15 ) 21...b3 $1 22.Nxb3 Nxa4 $17 ) 21.Qxc3 $2 ( { White should have taken with the rook: } 21.Rxc3 $11 { keeping equality thanks to ideas of Qb5 and Nc4. } ) 21...Qb8 22.Rff1 Nb4 23.Qc7 Qe8 { White's queen invasion doesn't achieve anything, as the queen has no good targets. } 24.Qb7 Rb8 25.Qa7 Ra8 26.Qb7 Rb8 27.Qa7 d5 28.exd5 Nxd5 $17 29.Bc5 $2 { A decisive mistake in a position that was already very tough for White. } 29...Ra8 $19 30.Qb7 Rb8 31.Qa7 Ra8 32.Qb7 Bxc5+ 33.Rxc5 Rb8 34.Qxf7+ Rxf7 35.Bxd5 Kh8 36.Rfc1 Rd7 37.Bc6 Qd8 38.Bxd7 Qxd7 39.Ne4 h5 

