 { In this game White didn't challenge Black's ...b5, ...Nbd7 setup and overextended on the kingside, resulting in the first player being comprehensively outplayed. Even though ..b4 was played without a2-a4 for White, making it possible for White to try and undermine the pawns with a2-a3, Black thought out the details well and navigated to an advantage. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nde2 Be7 8.Bg2 O-O 9.O-O b5 10.h3 $6 ( 10.Nd5 $1 Nbd7 11.Nec3 Nxd5 12.Nxd5 Nf6 $11 ) 10...Nbd7 11.g4 b4 12.Nd5 Nxd5 13.exd5 a5 14.Ng3 Nc5 15.Re1 Bg5 16.Bxg5 Qxg5 $17 17.a3 Rb8 ( 17...b3 $5 18.cxb3 f5 $1 $17 { was also a tempting shot. } ) 18.axb4 Rxb4 19.Rxa5 Rxb2 20.Re3 Bd7 21.Rea3 Rfb8 22.Ra8 Qd8 23.Rxb8 Qxb8 24.Kh2 Rb4 25.Qa1 Ra4 26.Rxa4 Bxa4 27.Ne4 Nxe4 28.Bxe4 Qb4 29.Qh1 Qc5 30.Bxh7+ Kxh7 31.Qe4+ f5 32.Qxa4 Qxf2+ 33.Kh1 Qf1+ 34.Kh2 Qf2+ 35.Kh1 Qe1+ 36.Kh2 f4 37.Qb3 e4 38.g5 Qf2+ 39.Kh1 f3 

