 { This game is an example of mishandling the variation by Black. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Bg2 O-O 9.O-O b5 ( 9...Nbd7 $6 10.a4 $1 b6 11.Nd2 $16 ) 10.a4 ( 10.Re1 { allows the rook to b8 later: } 10...Nbd7 11.a4 b4 12.Nd5 Nxd5 13.Qxd5 Rb8 $11 ) 10...b4 11.Nd5 Nxd5 12.Qxd5 Ra7 13.Be3 Be6 14.Qd3 Rb7 ( 14...Ra8 $1 { It's best to cover this a6 pawn and develop the knight to d7! } ) ( { Playing for ...d5 is wrong: } 14...Rd7 $6 15.Qe2 d5 16.exd5 Bxd5 17.Bxd5 Rxd5 18.Rfd1 Rxd1+ 19.Rxd1 Qc7 20.Rd5 $16 { Black has only created terrible weaknesses for himself. } ) 15.Rfc1 Qc7 16.c3 $1 { An amazing idea. Taking on b3 now is met with cxb4 and recapturing on b3! } 16...Bc4 17.Qc2 Be6 18.Qd1 Qd8 19.Bf1 bxc3 20.Rxc3 Bg5 21.Bxg5 Qxg5 22.Bc4 Bxc4 23.Rxc4 { And this is a typical White advantage because Black has many weaknesses around the board! } 23...Nd7 24.Rac1 Qd8 25.Rc6 Qb8 26.Rxd6 Rxb3 27.Rxd7 Rxb2 28.Qd5 Rb1 $2 ( 28...Qb6 $2 29.Rxf7 $18 ) ( { Only a stubborn move like } 28...h5 $16 { gave defensive chances. } ) 29.Rxb1 Qxb1+ 30.Kg2 $18 Qa1 31.a5 h6 32.Rd6 Rc8 33.Rxa6 Rc1 34.Ra8+ Kh7 35.Qxf7 

