 { This game shows that in the 7.Nde2 line, in the case of a quick g3-g4 expansion by White, Black can benefit from not castling short too early and exploiting White's overextended pawns. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nde2 Be7 8.Bg2 Nbd7 9.h3 b5 10.a3 Bb7 { Perhaps it was even more accurate to delay the bishop's development with one of two alternative moves. } ( 10...Nb6 ) ( 10...h5 ) 11.g4 Nb6 12.Ng3 g6 13.O-O h5 14.g5 Nfd7 15.h4 Rc8 16.Nd5 Nxd5 17.exd5 Rc4 18.f4 Qb6+ 19.Kh1 Qd4 20.Qxd4 Rxd4 21.b3 f5 $4 { A moment of blindness by both sides. } ( { Black should have played } 21...Bxd5 $11 ) 22.Be3 $4 ( { Both players missed } 22.Ne2 $1 Rxd5 23.c4 $1 $18 ) 22...Rxd5 23.Ne2 e4 24.Nc3 Rc5 25.Bxc5 Nxc5 $17 { Black has a tremendous compensation for the exchange. He went on to win convincingly. } 26.Rad1 Kd7 27.Nd5 Bxd5 28.Rxd5 Rc8 29.Rf2 Ne6 30.Bf1 Rc3 31.a4 Kc6 32.Rd1 Bd8 33.axb5+ axb5 34.Rfd2 Bc7 35.Rd5 Nxf4 36.Bxb5+ Kb6 37.Be8 Rh3+ 38.Kg1 Nxd5 39.Rxd5 f4 40.Bxg6 e3 41.Rd3 Rh1+ 42.Kxh1 e2 43.Kg2 e1=Q 

