 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nde2 ( 7.Nf5 { simply doesn't work tactically: } 7...d5 8.Bg5 d4 $17 9.Nd5 $2 Bxf5 $19 ) 7...Nbd7 8.Bg2 $6 ( 8.a4 $1 ) 8...Qc7 $6 ( 8...b5 $1 ) 9.O-O $6 ( 9.a4 $1 ) 9...b5 $1 { Finally!! Black has achieved what we want in the g3 Najdorf: ...Nbd7 and ...b5 both on the board BEFORE WHITE DOES SOMETHING ACTIVE! } 10.h3 h5 11.Bg5 Bb7 ( 11...Be7 $1 $15 { lets be a bit more flexible with our Bc8!! } ) 12.Qd2 Be7 13.Rfc1 Nb6 14.b3 g6 15.a3 O-O 16.Qe3 Rac8 17.Qf3 Kg7 18.Qe3 Rfd8 19.Rd1 Ng8 20.Bxe7 Nxe7 21.f4 f6 22.g4 hxg4 23.hxg4 Qc5 24.Qxc5 dxc5 25.fxe5 fxe5 26.Kf2 Nc6 27.Rxd8 Rxd8 28.Rd1 Nd4 29.Nxd4 cxd4 30.Nb1 Rc8 31.Rd2 Nd7 32.g5 Nc5 33.Re2 Ne6 34.Bh3 Rf8+ 35.Kg3 Nxg5 36.Bg2 Rc8 37.Kf2 Ne6 38.Bf3 Nf4 39.Rd2 Rh8 40.c3 Rh2+ 41.Ke1 Rh3 42.Kf2 d3 43.Ke3 g5 44.Kf2 Kg6 

