 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.g3 e5 7.Nde2 Be7 8.Bg2 O-O 9.O-O Be6 $5 { I prefer this way of development when White has a Nb3 instead of a Nde2. } ( 9...b5 10.Nd5 Nbd7 11.Nec3 Nxd5 12.Nxd5 Nf6 $11 ) 10.a4 Nbd7 11.a5 Rc8 12.Nd5 $2 { Black will now be able to exploit a number of weak squares created in White's camp. } 12...Nxd5 13.exd5 Bf5 14.c3 Rc5 $1 15.b4 Rc4 16.f4 Bg4 $1 17.Bd2 exf4 18.Rxf4 Ne5 $17 19.h3 Bd7 20.Rxc4 Nxc4 21.Nd4 $6 Nxd2 $1 { The bishop is even more important than our strong knight, as White now finds herself with tragically weak dark squares and a strategically lost position. } 22.Qxd2 Bg5 23.Qd3 Re8 $19 { All Black's long-range pieces are a tremendous force here, leaving White hopeless, even though it might not seem so clear at first sight. } 24.Nc2 Qc8 25.Re1 Rxe1+ 26.Nxe1 Bb5 27.c4 Qxc4 28.Qxc4 Be3+ 29.Kh2 Bxc4 30.Nc2 Bd2 31.Be4 g6 32.g4 Kg7 33.Kg3 Kf6 34.Na3 Bb3 35.b5 Bxa5 36.bxa6 bxa6 37.Bd3 Bb4 38.Nc4 a5 39.Kf4 a4 40.g5+ Ke7 41.Ne3 a3 42.Bc2 a2 

