 { In the Najdorf, White has many options on move 6. In this lecture, we will check some of the rare lines for White. Against all of them, I suggest to play with the e7-e5. After the moves: } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 { In this lecture, I analyzed: } 6.Rg1 ( 6.a3 { It just looks like a waste of time. Black should be more than OK after: } 6...e5 7.Nf5 { Is not working, because Black can continue with: } 7...d5 $1 $15 ) ( 6.h4 { This becomes fashionable recently, but Black is doing well after the typical: } 6...e5 7.Nb3 h6 $1 { stopping Bg5 } ) ( 6.f4 e5 7.Nf3 Qc7 $1 ) ( 6.a4 { is a positional system. Black should continue: } 6...e5 7.Nf3 ( 7.Nb3 Be6 $1 { Intedning fast developing of the queenside } ) 7...Qc7 { Is the correct move with a decent play } ) 

