[Site "Turin"]

 { [%evp 0,24,35,32,46,43,91,64,64,36,34,26,44,-5,-1,6,8,11,13,22,17,26,64,50,50, 39,48] } 1.e4 c5 $1 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.h4 { this move became fashionable some years ago..but it is not something special...just a playable Najdorf move } ( 6.f4 e5 $1 { Simplest and most direct! } ( 6...e6 $6 { a bit passive for no reason! If we have a choice we should prefer ...e5 } 7.Qf3 ) ( 6...Qc7 { this is also interesting and popular. Intending g6-Bg7 } ) 7.Nf3 ( 7.Nf5 $2 Nc6 $1 $15 { By far the best move. } ( 7...d5 8.Be3 ( 8.fxe5 Nxe4 9.Nxe4 Bxf5 10.Ng3 Bg6 $15 ) ( 8.Ne3 Bb4 $1 ( 8...exf4 9.Nexd5 Nxd5 10.Nxd5 Qh4+ 11.g3 fxg3 12.Nc7+ Ke7 ) 9.Nexd5 Nxe4 ) 8...Bxf5 9.exf5 Bd6 $1 $15 ) 8.fxe5 Nxe4 $15 ) ( 7.Nb3 $6 { Clearly not the best. } 7...Nbd7 { Intending b5 next. } ( 7...Nc6 $1 { this is also very simple and good here .. because this Nc6 will soon go to e5 } ) 8.Bd3 ( 8.a4 { usually the best move, stopping b5. } 8...Be7 9.Bd3 O-O 10.O-O b6 ( 10...exf4 $5 11.Bxf4 Ne5 $132 12.Kh1 Be6 13.Nd4 Qc7 ) 11.Be3 Bb7 $132 ) ( 8.g4 $5 { an interesting attempt but it fails! } 8...d5 $3 9.g5 ( 9.exd5 Nb6 { very strong move. Black is better } 10.g5 ( 10.fxe5 Nfxd5 $15 ) 10...Nfxd5 11.Bg2 Nxf4 $132 ) 9...Nxe4 ) 8...b5 9.O-O Bb7 ( 9...Be7 { is also possible } 10.f5 Bb7 11.g4 b4 ( 11...h6 { Planning Rc8-Rxc3 is also possible. } ) ) 10.Kh1 Be7 $15 { We have reached the perfect najdorf set-up. a6-b5-nbd7-bb7-be7-0-0 with a weak pawn on e4 for white. } ) 7...Qc7 { rare and good! Stopping any Bc4 ideas! } ( 7...Nbd7 { is playable but I don't like to allow } 8.Bc4 ) 8.Bd3 Nbd7 9.a4 ( 9.O-O b5 $1 10.Kh1 ( 10.Nh4 g6 11.Kh1 Bg7 $36 ) 10...Be7 $132 ) 9...Be7 { but not 9...b6? } ( 9...b6 $2 10.Qe2 Bb7 11.O-O Be7 12.fxe5 dxe5 13.Nh4 $16 ) 10.O-O O-O 11.Kh1 { White's plan is Qe1-Qg3 and attack Black's King. } 11...Nc5 12.Qe1 Re8 { we prepare our defenses for a while. .and then we take on f4! } 13.fxe5 ( 13.Be3 exf4 { is also possible } ( 13...Bd7 14.fxe5 dxe5 15.Qg3 Bd8 { protecting everything. Strategically, Black is better here but White also has some attacking ideas. } ) 14.Bxf4 Bd7 $132 15.Nd4 Rac8 ( 15...Bd8 ) ) ( 13.Bd2 Bd7 { In this structure we don't want to keep our bishop on e6, as White can player f5. Instead, we are planning Bc6. } 14.a5 Rac8 $15 15.b4 ( 15.f5 Bc6 { Planning d5 } ) 15...Nxd3 16.cxd3 exf4 ) 13...dxe5 14.Qg3 Bd8 $1 $132 { The key move. The bishop from d8 has many functions. It is protecting the queen to avoid Nd4-Nf5 tricks, stopping Rxf6 ideas. } 15.Bg5 Be6 16.Qxe5 Qxe5 17.Nxe5 Ng4 18.Bxd8 ( 18.Nxg4 Bxg5 $17 { Although, Black is a pawn down his activity pieces compensate that. } 19.Ne5 Bf6 20.Nf3 Bxc3 21.bxc3 Bd7 ) 18...Nxe5 $17 ) ( 6.a4 { simple positional line } 6...e5 ( 6...g6 $5 { it makes sense to go for a Dragon Sicilian..now that White has lost his most dangerous ideas involving 0-0-0. However, I decided to stick to the typical Najdorf approach. } ) 7.Nf3 ( 7.Nb3 Be6 $1 { Intending a fast Nbd7 } ( 7...Be7 $5 { this is also totally playable of course....with typical Najdorf play! } 8.Bg5 ) 8.f4 ( 8.Be2 Nbd7 9.O-O Rc8 10.a5 Be7 { Transposing to Najdorf 6.Be2 } ) 8...exf4 9.Bxf4 { When white recaptures this pawn on f4, he usually wants to castle long. But since he has already committed with ..a4 this is no longer a favourable choice. } 9...Nc6 10.Be2 Be7 $1 ( 10...d5 $1 11.exd5 Nxd5 12.Nxd5 Bxd5 13.O-O Be7 $132 ) 11.O-O O-O $132 12.Kh1 d5 $1 $132 ( 12...Rc8 $1 $132 ) 13.e5 Ne4 $3 $15 14.Bd3 f5 15.exf6 Nxf6 16.Qe2 Qd7 $15 17.Rae1 Bf7 ( 17...Bg4 ) ) 7...Qc7 $5 ( 7...Be6 $6 ) ( 7...h6 $5 { the usual .. lazy solution in the Nf3 lines ! ....h6-Be6 } 8.Bc4 Be7 9.O-O Be6 $1 10.Qe2 O-O 11.Be3 Qc7 12.Bb3 Nc6 $1 $132 ) 8.Bg5 ( 8.Be3 Be7 ) 8...Nbd7 9.Nd2 h6 10.Bh4 ( 10.Be3 Nc5 11.Be2 Be6 $132 ) 10...g5 11.Bg3 Nc5 12.Qf3 Bg7 $1 ( 12...Be7 ) 13.Bc4 Be6 14.Bxe6 fxe6 $36 15.O-O O-O 16.Qe2 Qc6 $15 ) ( 6.a3 $6 { This is more like a waste of time..it can be useful only to prevent some Bb4 by black in some concrete position..but black has other ways to play..making the a3 move irrelevant } 6...e5 7.Nf5 $6 ( 7.Nb3 Be7 ) ( 7.Nf3 h6 ( 7...Be7 ) ( 7...Qc7 ) ) 7...d5 $1 { Black is simply better. } ( 7...Bxf5 8.exf5 d5 9.Bg5 Bb4 { Normally in this position our move would be Bb4, However this is not possible now. } 10.axb4 { This is the idea of 6.a3?! .....to stop Bb4 here } ) 8.Bg5 d4 9.Bxf6 ( 9.Nd5 $4 Bxf5 $1 $19 { Black wins a piece. } ) 9...gxf6 10.Na2 $5 ( 10.Ne2 Qb6 $17 ( 10...h5 11.h4 Qb6 12.b4 Qc6 $17 ) ( 10...Qa5+ $17 11.c3 ( 11.Qd2 Qxd2+ 12.Kxd2 Nd7 ) 11...Bxf5 12.exf5 Nc6 $17 ) 11.Rb1 Be6 12.Nc1 Bxa3 ) ( 10.Nb1 Bxf5 ( 10...Qb6 $15 ) 11.exf5 Qd5 $15 12.Qd3 Nd7 { Black is again better. } 13.Nd2 ( 13.b4 e4 $4 ( 13...a5 $17 ) ) 13...Nc5 ) 10...Bxf5 11.exf5 Qd5 12.Be2 e4 $15 ) ( 6.Rg1 e5 $1 { again the most direct approach! . } 7.Nb3 { the only meaningful move } ( 7.Nf3 $6 Be7 $15 ) ( 7.Nf5 $2 d5 $17 8.g4 d4 ) 7...h5 $1 { a typical Najdorf move! . } 8.Bg5 { This appears to be the most natural move..and yet it's not the best! 8.h3 or 8.Be3 is better } ( 8.h3 $5 Be6 $1 ( 8...h4 $5 ) 9.Qf3 ( 9.g4 hxg4 $1 { DONT FORGET TO OPPEN THE FILE FOR THE ROOK IN THE COMPLICATIONS!! } 10.hxg4 d5 11.exd5 ( 11.g5 Nxe4 ) 11...Nxd5 12.Nxd5 Qxd5 $1 13.Qxd5 Bxd5 14.Be3 Nc6 15.O-O-O O-O-O 16.Bb6 Rd7 17.Be2 ( 17.Nc5 $6 Rd6 $3 $15 18.Nb3 Be7 19.Bc5 Bg5+ 20.Kb1 Rd7 21.Be2 Kc7 $3 $17 ) 17...Be7 $132 18.g5 Be6 ) 9...h4 $3 { try to remember..and not to mix the lines ! .. .this is the Najdorf! ..no room for such mistakes!! } ( 9...d5 $2 10.exd5 Nxd5 11.Bc4 Nxc3 12.Bxe6 $16 ) 10.Bg5 ( 10.Be3 Nbd7 11.O-O-O Rc8 $15 ) ( 10.Bd2 Nbd7 11.O-O-O Rc8 $36 ) 10...Be7 11.O-O-O Nbd7 $132 ) ( 8.Be3 Be6 9.Qd2 ( 9.h3 Nbd7 10.g4 hxg4 11.hxg4 Rc8 $1 $15 12.g5 Rxc3 $3 13.gxf6 ( 13.bxc3 Nxe4 $17 ) 13...Rxe3+ $3 14.fxe3 Nxf6 $17 15.Qf3 Qc8 ) 9...Nbd7 10.f3 ( 10.O-O-O Ng4 $1 $132 11.Bg5 f6 12.Be3 Nxh2 $5 ) 10...Be7 11.O-O-O b5 $132 ) 8...Be6 9.Qd2 ( 9.Bxf6 $2 { SUPER SOS !! In most cases this strategy is connected with short casting for white! ..but here he has lost this right! HOWEVER, MANY PLAYERS WITH THE WHITE PIECES WILL BE CONFUSED AND PLAY LIKE THIS ! } 9...Qxf6 10.Nd5 ( 10.Na5 $2 Qd8 $1 11.Nc4 g6 $3 $17 12.Qd3 b5 13.Ne3 Nd7 $17 14.O-O-O Rb8 $17 ( 14...b4 15.Ncd5 Nc5 ) ) 10...Qd8 11.Qd2 ( 11.c3 g6 $17 12.Be2 Nd7 13.Qd3 Nb6 $3 $17 ( 13...Bh6 ) ) 11...g6 $15 { white cannot castle either side } ) 9...Nbd7 10.O-O-O b5 11.f4 ( 11.f3 Be7 $132 { we have a good version of the 6.Be3-e5 7.Nb3-Be6 8.f3-h5 Najdorf ! } 12.a3 Rb8 $36 ) 11...Be7 12.f5 $2 ( 12.Bd3 $1 O-O $132 13.f5 Bc4 ) ( 12.Kb1 $1 b4 ( 12...Rc8 $132 ) 13.Bxf6 Nxf6 14.Nd5 Bxd5 15.exd5 Qb6 16.Bc4 O-O $1 $132 ) 12...Bxb3 $3 $17 { A VERY CONCRETE LINE !! } 13.axb3 ( 13.cxb3 $2 b4 14.Nd5 Nxd5 $19 ) 13...Qa5 $3 14.Kb1 b4 15.Nd5 Nxd5 16.exd5 Bxg5 17.Qxg5 Nf6 $3 $17 18.Qxg7 ( 18.Bc4 Kf8 $3 $17 19.Qe3 Rb8 20.h3 h4 $17 ( 20...Qb6 ) ) 18...Ke7 19.Qg5 Qc5 20.Bc4 Rhg8 21.Qd2 a5 $17 { Najdorf 6.Rg1-e5 -FULL THEORY /chess.com INT 0/[,ГйЬннзт] } ) 6...e5 { again the most direct approach } ( 6...h6 $1 { is a usefull waiting move .. leading to unclear play } ) ( 6...Nc6 $1 { is totally plyable alternative } 7.f3 e5 ) 7.Nb3 { The only move that makes sense. } 7...h6 $5 { an interesting little move. ..avoiding Bg5 ....if white can afford an h4 move ...we can also move our -h- pawn a bit early ! } 8.Be3 ( 8.f3 $6 Nh5 $1 9.Be3 Ng3 10.Rh2 ( 10.Rg1 Be6 $1 11.Nd5 Nd7 $15 12.Qd2 Nxf1 13.Rxf1 Qxh4+ 14.Rf2 Qd8 ) 10...Nxf1 11.Kxf1 Be6 12.Qd2 Nd7 13.Rd1 Rc8 $15 ) 8...Be7 9.f3 ( 9.Be2 $6 Be6 10.Qd2 Nbd7 11.f4 b5 $1 $15 ( 11...Rc8 $15 ) 12.f5 Bc4 ) 9...Be6 10.Qd2 ( 10.g4 d5 $36 ) 10...h5 $5 11.O-O-O Nbd7 12.Kb1 b5 $132 { with typical Najdorf counter-play } 

*

