 { [%evp 0,49,16,28,97,43,86,49,55,52,38,34,58,-16,19,-2,48,60,53,-1,158,112,109, 131,124,132,134,134,147,116,105,107,131,122,94,90,133,112,144,141,138,160,186, 176,234,232,183,186,193,204,191,205] Important game for theory. } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.f4 { This move was very popular 25 years ago. Generally, my approach would be to play ..e5 against such sidelines whenever possible. } 6...e5 7.Nb3 Qc7 ( 7...Nbd7 $1 8.g4 ( 8.Bc4 $2 { The bishop is unstable on d5. } 8...b5 9.Bd5 Rb8 $1 $15 { We don't take the bishop yet! White's pieces are unstable. } 10.a3 { Sooner or later we will play a5-b4. } ) ( 8.Bd3 b5 ) ( 8.a4 Be7 9.Bd3 b6 ( 9...O-O 10.O-O exf4 { we can also play this way. } 11.Bxf4 Ne5 12.Kh1 Be6 ) 10.O-O Bb7 ) 8...d5 $3 9.exd5 Nb6 $3 $132 ) 8.Be2 Nbd7 ( 8...Be7 9.g4 ) 9.g4 $1 { White is now better and in the end he won the game. } 9...h6 ( 9...b5 $3 10.g5 $6 ( 10.a3 Bb7 11.Bf3 Nb6 12.g5 Nfd7 13.Na5 Na4 $3 ) 10...b4 11.gxf6 bxc3 $15 ) 10.g5 hxg5 11.fxg5 Ng8 12.Nd5 Qd8 13.Be3 Ne7 14.h4 Nxd5 15.Qxd5 Nb6 16.Qa5 Nd7 17.Qxd8+ Kxd8 18.O-O-O Ke8 19.Bc4 Nb8 20.h5 Be6 21.Na5 Bg4 22.Rdf1 Be6 23.Bxe6 fxe6 24.Nxb7 Nc6 25.Rd1 

