 { [%evp 0,26,20,21,37,37,57,57,57,32,32,26,52,38,16,39,33,9,21,10,10,10,35,11,8, 8,8,9,-10] } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Nb3 $5 { This is one of the best rare moves ...we will soon reach an unclear and complicated position with chances for both sides! It would be pointless once again to try to memorize every possible move and idea ! } ( 6.Qf3 $6 { one of the most unfortunate 6th moves by white in the Najdorf! The queen is very misplaced there ..and black has a very good chance to quickly size the initiative! ...he just needs to know a few good moves! } 6...g6 $1 { the best move } ( 6...Qb6 $1 { is another playable line } 7.Nb3 Nbd7 $132 8.Be3 Qc7 { These positions are quite fresh and unexplored. } 9.a4 ( 9.O-O-O b5 $36 ) 9...g6 $1 $132 10.Bd3 Bg7 11.O-O Ne5 ) 7.h3 { sooner or later this has to be played! } 7...Bg7 { e5 is also playable. } 8.Be3 { intending 0-0-0 } ( 8.Bg5 Bd7 9.O-O-O Nc6 $36 ) 8...O-O 9.O-O-O Nc6 $36 { Bd7 is also possible. } 10.g4 ( 10.Nd5 Nxd5 11.exd5 Ne5 12.Qe2 b5 $40 ) ( 10.Nxc6 $2 bxc6 11.e5 $2 Nd5 $17 12.Nxd5 cxd5 13.exd6 Rb8 { with very strong attack. } 14.c3 e6 $19 15.Bc5 Qa5 16.Ba3 Bd7 $19 ) 10...Bd7 $1 11.Qg2 ( 11.g5 Nh5 $17 ) 11...b5 $36 { 6.Qf3/[,ГйЬннзт] } ( 11...Rc8 $15 ) ( 11...Nxd4 12.Bxd4 e5 13.Be3 Rc8 $36 14.f3 Rxc3 15.bxc3 Qa5 $15 ) ) ( 6.Bd3 { This is another fashionable line without deep ideas. The idea is to just develop the pieces and play chess! Quite often White's Knight from d4 will go to e2 and then to g3 for kingside attacks. We hope that this Ng3 will turn out to be misplaced. } 6...e5 $1 ( 6...g6 $5 { A simple and good move, not much theory is needed after that. We just play natural moves in the center. } 7.f3 $1 ( 7.O-O Bg7 8.h3 O-O 9.Be3 Nc6 $132 ( 9...b5 $5 10.a4 b4 11.Na2 ( 11.Nd5 Nxd5 12.exd5 Bb7 $15 ) 11...e5 12.Nb3 Nc6 $132 ) 10.Nb3 Be6 $132 ( 10...b5 $132 ) ) ( 7.h3 { white plays for long castling ... } 7...Bg7 8.Be3 O-O 9.Qd2 b5 $1 ( 9...Nc6 10.O-O-O Bd7 $132 ) ( 9...Nbd7 $5 10.O-O-O b5 $132 ) 10.O-O-O $6 Bb7 11.f3 Nbd7 $15 12.h4 b4 13.Nce2 e5 14.Nb3 a5 $36 ) 7...Qb6 $1 8.a3 ( 8.Nb3 Bg7 9.Qe2 Nc6 10.Be3 Qc7 11.O-O-O b5 $132 ) 8...Nc6 $5 ( 8...Nbd7 $5 9.Be3 e5 10.Nf5 Nc5 $132 ) 9.Be3 ( 9.Nxc6 bxc6 $36 ) 9...e5 $1 10.Nf5 Qd8 11.Ng3 ( 11.Nh6 Nh5 12.Ng4 Be6 $132 13.Qd2 ( 13.O-O f5 ) 13...f5 14.Bg5 Be7 15.Bxe7 Qxe7 ) 11...Be6 12.Qd2 Bg7 13.O-O-O O-O $132 ) 7.Nde2 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Ng3 ( 9.a4 Nc6 $1 10.Ng3 Nb4 $132 ) ( 9.h3 { white is waiting a bit with f4 } 9...Nc6 10.f4 b5 $1 $132 ) ( 9.f4 $6 Nbd7 10.Ng3 Nc5 $132 ) 9...Be6 $1 { this is the most natural move } ( 9...Re8 $5 { another interesting waiting move ! } ) 10.Nd5 ( 10.Nf5 $2 Bxf5 11.exf5 d5 12.Bg5 Nbd7 $17 ) 10...Bxd5 11.exd5 g6 $1 12.c4 Nbd7 $132 { black has a very good game More concrete theory is pointless now.... here are some sample lines : } 13.Bh6 ( 13.Kh1 Re8 14.f4 Bf8 $1 15.fxe5 Nxe5 16.Bg5 Be7 $3 $15 ) ( 13.b3 h5 14.Ne2 Nh7 $132 ) 13...Re8 14.Re1 ( 14.Qd2 $2 Ng4 $17 ) 14...Bf8 ( 14...a5 $5 $132 { is another good idea ! } ) 15.Bg5 h6 16.Be3 h5 $132 ) 6...Nc6 $1 ( 6...g6 $1 { this is another very logical move the play is now in the fields of the dragon sicilian ! } 7.Be2 Bg7 8.O-O O-O 9.Be3 Nc6 $132 ) ( 6...e6 $1 { is another very logical idea } 7.g4 b5 8.a3 ( 8.g5 b4 $132 { is the reason why the e6 setup works. } ( 8...Nfd7 9.Bg2 Bb7 10.Be3 Nc6 $132 ) ) 8...Bb7 9.Bg2 Nfd7 $5 10.g5 Nc6 11.Be3 Be7 $132 { and soon Nb6 !-Nc4 } ) ( 6...e5 $2 { unfortunately this is not working here ! } 7.Bg5 Be6 8.f4 exf4 9.Qd2 $16 ) 7.Be3 $1 { this is the best ..intending to go for 0-0-0 } ( 7.Be2 { Here are some sample lines! ..in all these Shevenigen positions the Nb3 is misplaced and black has good counter play ! } 7...e6 $1 8.O-O ( 8.g4 h6 $132 9.Be3 b5 ) 8...Be7 9.a4 b6 10.f4 Bb7 11.Bf3 O-O $132 ) ( 7.f3 e6 ( 7...g6 $132 ) 8.Be3 b5 9.Qd2 Be7 ( 9...Bb7 ) ( 9...Ne5 $1 10.O-O-O Bd7 $132 ) ( 9...Bd7 $1 { intending after a b4 move to stop Na4 } 10.O-O-O Ne5 11.a3 Rb8 12.Qe1 Qc7 13.f4 Nc4 14.Bxc4 bxc4 15.Nd2 Be7 16.e5 dxe5 17.fxe5 Nd5 18.Bd4 O-O 19.Nde4 Kh8 20.Qg3 Bc6 21.Nxd5 Bxd5 22.Nf6 Bxf6 23.exf6 Qxg3 24.hxg3 g5 25.Rh5 Rg8 26.Re1 Bxg2 27.Kd2 Rg6 28.Kc3 Bd5 29.Be5 Rc8 30.Re3 h6 31.g4 Kh7 32.Reh3 Bg2 33.Rg3 Bd5 34.Rgh3 Bg2 35.Rg3 Bd5 36.Bd4 Re8 37.Re3 Rb8 38.Be5 Rb7 39.Reh3 Bg2 40.Rg3 Bd5 41.Rh2 Kg8 42.Bd4 Rb8 43.Rgh3 Kh7 44.Be3 Rxf6 45.Bxg5 Rf3+ 46.Rxf3 Bxf3 47.Rxh6+ Kg7 48.Rh4 f6 49.Bh6+ Kf7 50.Be3 Rg8 51.g5 fxg5 52.Rxc4 g4 53.Bf2 Rh8 54.Kd2 Rh3 55.Rf4+ Kg6 56.Bd4 Rh2+ 57.Kd3 Re2 58.Rf6+ Kg5 59.Rf8 e5 60.Be3+ { 1/2-1/2 Madaminov, M-Abdurakhmonov, M/Khiva UZB 2022 } ) 10.g4 b4 11.Ne2 Nd7 $36 ) ( 7.Bd3 e6 ( 7...g6 $5 8.O-O Bg7 9.Re1 O-O 10.h3 b5 $132 ) 8.O-O Be7 9.f4 O-O 10.Qf3 ( 10.a3 b5 11.Qf3 Bb7 $132 ) 10...Bd7 11.Kh1 Nb4 $132 ( 11...b5 ) ) 7...e6 { We are forced to follow the e6 setup. } 8.g4 $1 ( 8.f4 b5 9.Qf3 Bb7 10.O-O-O Qc7 $132 { Check Kasparov games as Black to master this structure. } ) ( 8.Qe2 b5 $132 ) 8...h6 { Black can also ignore this pawn storm with ...b5 } 9.Qe2 $1 { this is probably the best ....and here is some. simple lines once again! ...all of them with typical unclear play and chances for both sides ! ..... that was the idea after 6.Nb3! anyway ! } ( 9.Bg2 $6 { SUPER SOS !! THIS IS THE VERY TYPICAL MISTAKE THAT EVERYONE MAKES IN THESE POSITIONS! ...THE BISHOP IS VERY BADLY PLACED ON g2 BECAUSE IT ABANDONS c4 Square !! } 9...Ne5 10.h3 Bd7 $15 ( 10...b5 $15 ) 11.Nd2 g5 ) ( 9.h3 b5 10.Qe2 Bb7 11.O-O-O Qc7 $132 ) 9...b5 10.O-O-O ( 10.a3 Bb7 11.O-O-O Rc8 12.Nc5 Qc7 13.Nxb7 Qxb7 $132 ) 10...Qc7 $132 ( 10...b4 $5 11.Na4 ( 11.Nb1 $2 a5 $15 ) 11...Rb8 12.f3 Qc7 13.Qf2 Ne5 $132 ) 11.f4 ( 11.Bg2 $2 { White should not abondan the c4-square. } 11...b4 12.Na4 Rb8 $36 ) ( 11.f3 Rb8 $5 12.Qf2 Ne5 $36 ) 11...b4 12.Na4 Rb8 $132 13.Bg2 e5 $3 { 6.Nb3 / chess.com INT 0/[,ГйЬннзт] } 

