 { [%evp 0,63,16,28,46,51,91,56,80,57,57,39,77,16,48,55,104,89,67,41,31,4,53,59, 44,58,82,88,88,68,122,82,188,184,118,161,147,147,217,-2,0,57,41,41,55,55,15, -74,2,25,59,30,0,0,0,34,198,272,487,471,471,471,471,461,461,461] } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Qf3 Nbd7 7.Be2 e6 $2 { This is an example of how not to play! Generally , in all these sublines, it is best to avoid the e6 Shevenigen set-ups, because they tend to give White an easier game than he deserves! } ( 7...g6 { would have been better. We have two ideas: Bg7 or e5-Be7 } ) 8.Be3 Qc7 9.g4 h6 ( 9...Ne5 { is not doing anything after } 10.Qg2 { intending g5-f4. } ) 10.Qh3 Nc5 11.f3 { White is doing more than he deserves. } 11...b5 12.g5 b4 13.gxf6 bxc3 14.b4 e5 15.Qg3 Ne6 16.Nxe6 fxe6 17.f4 gxf6 18.fxe5 dxe5 19.Rd1 Qf7 20.Bb6 Be7 21.Rg1 Bb7 22.Qh3 h5 23.Qd3 f5 24.exf5 Bh4+ 25.Rg3 exf5 26.Qxc3 Qg7 27.Qb3 Rh6 28.Bc5 Bc8 29.Qd5 Rb8 30.Kf1 Bxg3 31.Qd8+ Kf7 32.hxg3 

